{"title_page": "Training needs analysis", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{technical|date=August 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Training Analysis''' (sometimes called '''Training Needs Analysis''' (TNA)) is the process of identifying the gap in employee training and related training needs.\n\n== Introduction ==\nTraining Need Analysis (TNA) is the process of identifying the gap between employee training and needs of training. Training needs analysis is the first stage in the training process and involves a series of steps that reveal whether training will help to solve problem which has been identified. Training can be described as \u201cthe acquisition of skills, concepts or attitudes that result in improved performance within the job environment\u201d. Training needs analysis looks at each side of operational area of job so that the  concepts and attitudes of the human elements of a system can be effectively identified and appropriate training can be specified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirjournal.com/guides/how-to-conduct-a-training-needs-analysis/|title=How to Conduct a Training Needs Analysis|publisher=Directory Journal|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTraining needs analysis is most often used as part of the system development process. Due to the close tie between the design of the system and the training required, in most cases it runs alongside the development to capture the training requirements.needs additional citations for verification\n\n==Design Integrated Training Analysis==\nTools and methods for an integrated approach, [[Design Integrated Training Analysis]], have been proposed and developed. The trade-offs between design and training are both assessed in light of the understanding of the operational tasks. This approach also uses information on recorded critical incidents to review proposed training and to provide traceability between hazards and training. This single, integrated approach to human factors and training needs analysis has been successfully used on a number of defence projects.\n\n==Training Analysis Process==\nOver the last 20 years the critical nature of the [[man-in-the-loop]] has changed from simply manual dexterity and procedural operation to a state in which their decision making, cognitive abilities, [[data assimilation]], communication skills, and attitude are all crucial. In addition the job structure of the personnel operationally involved with modern systems has diversified in direct proportion to the complexity of the technology.   This has fueled the need for a formal approach.\n\nThe task of training can be broken down into a number of discrete components, each addressing a different part of the overall learning process. This breakdown is as follows:-\n* Psycho-motor Skills\n* Procedural Skills\n* Knowledge Transfer\n* Communication Skills\n* Colossal Thinking\n* Attitude Learning\n* Performance Training\n* Physiological Stresses\n\nThe role of training analysis is to build a formal bridge between the available design data and the training media and training objectives, in order to facilitate the [[transfer of training]] elements into the operational environment.\n\nFor complex multi-user system a user-to-task map is often constructed to present the relationship between the tasks and the identified team structure and also to identify new groups of users that would need to have an understanding of the system. The training gap is assessed by a comparison between the goals and tasks undertaken by the individuals and the existing training.\n\nThere is a wide variety of training media that can be used, ranging from traditional lecture-based teaching to sophisticated simulators. Different media will be more or less appropriate for different activities. It is necessary to determine the most suitable and cost-effective training media for the different areas.\n\nThere have been many different approaches defined, however, the system approach to training has been the most successful.\n\nTraining Needs Analysis (TNA) is defined as the \u201cIdentification of training requirements and the most cost effective means of meeting those requirements\u201d.\n\nA TNA should always be performed where a major new development in policy, equipment acquisition or procedures is deemed to have potential impact upon the current training regime.\n\nTST has considerable experience of successfully employing the accepted techniques applied to the development of training systems, including the [[Systems Approach to Training]] (SAT) in both the defence and civilian domains using customer specific standards such as JSP 822 where required.\n\nCarrying out all TNA activates in accordance with SAT principles ensures rigorous visibility in each design stage with clear audit trails from the initial Scoping Study through to the recommended solution.\n\n== Benefits ==\n* Speed up the transition of adopting change\n* Reduce the risk and impact on the business and ensure that your people are not only prepared for the change but fully equipped\n* Help the trainee to achieve his goals and dreams in life.\n\n==See also  ==\n* [[Training]]\n* [[System design]]\n* [[Human factors]]\n* [[People Capability Maturity Model]]\n* [[Needs analysis]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.trainsmartinc.com/why-conduct-a-training-needs-assessment/ Why Conduct A Training Needs Analysis] A TrainSmart article\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Training Needs Analysis}}\n[[Category:Career and technical education]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{technical|date=August 2010}}\n}}\n\n'''Training Analysis''' (sometimes called '''Training Needs Analysis''' (TNA)) is the process of identifying the gap in employee training and related training needs.\n\n== Introduction ==needs additional citations for verification\nTraining Need Analysis (TNA) is the process of identifying the gap between employee training and needs of training. Training needs analysis is the first stage in the training process and involves a series of steps that reveal whether training will help to solve problem which has been identified. Training can be described as \u201cthe acquisition of skills, concepts or attitudes that result in improved performance within the job environment\u201d. Training needs analysis looks at each side of operational area of job so that the  concepts and attitudes of the human elements of a system can be effectively identified and appropriate training can be specified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirjournal.com/guides/how-to-conduct-a-training-needs-analysis/|title=How to Conduct a Training Needs Analysis|publisher=Directory Journal|accessdate=April 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTraining needs analysis is most often used as part of the system development process. Due to the close tie between the design of the system and the training required, in most cases it runs alongside the development to capture the training requirements.needs additional citations for verification\n\n==Design Integrated Training Analysis==\nTools and methods for an integrated approach, [[Design Integrated Training Analysis]], have been proposed and developed. The trade-offs between design and training are both assessed in light of the understanding of the operational tasks. This approach also uses information on recorded critical incidents to review proposed training and to provide traceability between hazards and training. This single, integrated approach to human factors and training needs analysis has been successfully used on a number of defence projects.\n\n==Training Analysis Process==\nOver the last 20 years the critical nature of the [[man-in-the-loop]] has changed from simply manual dexterity and procedural operation to a state in which their decision making, cognitive abilities, [[data assimilation]], communication skills, and attitude are all crucial. In addition the job structure of the personnel operationally involved with modern systems has diversified in direct proportion to the complexity of the technology.   This has fueled the need for a formal approach.\n\nThe task of training can be broken down into a number of discrete components, each addressing a different part of the overall learning process. This breakdown is as follows:-\n* Psycho-motor Skills\n* Procedural Skills\n* Knowledge Transfer\n* Communication Skills\n* Colossal Thinking\n* Attitude Learning\n* Performance Training\n* Physiological Stresses\n\nThe role of training analysis is to build a formal bridge between the available design data and the training media and training objectives, in order to facilitate the [[transfer of training]] elements into the operational environment.\n\nFor complex multi-user system a user-to-task map is often constructed to present the relationship between the tasks and the identified team structure and also to identify new groups of users that would need to have an understanding of the system. The training gap is assessed by a comparison between the goals and tasks undertaken by the individuals and the existing training.\n\nThere is a wide variety of training media that can be used, ranging from traditional lecture-based teaching to sophisticated simulators. Different media will be more or less appropriate for different activities. It is necessary to determine the most suitable and cost-effective training media for the different areas.\n\nThere have been many different approaches defined, however, the system approach to training has been the most successful.\n\nTraining Needs Analysis (TNA) is defined as the \u201cIdentification of training requirements and the most cost effective means of meeting those requirements\u201d.\n\nA TNA should always be performed where a major new development in policy, equipment acquisition or procedures is deemed to have potential impact upon the current training regime.\n\nTST has considerable experience of successfully employing the accepted techniques applied to the development of training systems, including the [[Systems Approach to Training]] (SAT) in both the defence and civilian domains using customer specific standards such as JSP 822 where required.\n\nCarrying out all TNA activates in accordance with SAT principles ensures rigorous visibility in each design stage with clear audit trails from the initial Scoping Study through to the recommended solution.\n\n== Benefits ==\n* Speed up the transition of adopting change\n* Reduce the risk and impact on the business and ensure that your people are not only prepared for the change but fully equipped\n* Help the trainee to achieve his goals and dreams in life.\n\n==See also  ==\n* [[Training]]\n* [[System design]]\n* [[Human factors]]\n* [[People Capability Maturity Model]]\n* [[Needs analysis]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.trainsmartinc.com/why-conduct-a-training-needs-assessment/ Why Conduct A Training Needs Analysis] A TrainSmart article\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Training Needs Analysis}}\n[[Category:Career and technical education]]\n", "name_user": "O-dog222", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed introduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Training_needs_analysis"}
{"title_page": "Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{COI|date=October 2018}}\n{{short description|Scandal in the United Kingdom about contaminated blood Red}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox event \n| title                    = Contaminated Blood Scandal HIV\n| image                    = Bottles of factor viii haemophilia treatment.jpg\n| caption                  = Bottle of Factor VIII, a product used to treat haemophilia\n| date                     = 1970s & 1980s\n| place                    = [[United Kingdom]]\n| cause                    = Contaminated Factor VIII & Factor IX\n| reported death(s)        = 1,246+\n| inquiries                = [[Contaminated blood scandal inquiry|Contaminated Blood Scandal Inquiry]]\n| suspects                 =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n}}\nThe '''Contaminated Blood Scandal''' in the United Kingdom arose when at least 3,891 people, most of whom suffered from [[haemophilia]], became infected with [[hepatitis C]] of whom 1,243 were also infected with [[HIV]], the virus that leads to [[HIV/AIDS|acquired immune deficiency syndrome]] (AIDS), as a result of receiving [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|contaminated clotting factor products]] supplied by the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) in the 1970s and 1980s. As of October 2017 there were at least 1,246 confirmed deaths in the UK of people who were killed by the clotting agents Factor VIII & Factor IX and the viruses they transmitted. Some have estimated that the total number of those who have died could be as high as 2,400 though exact figures are not known.\n\nDuring the 1970s and 1980s, some people were infected with Hepatitis C via blood transfusions under entirely different circumstances. However, the Factor Concentrate products used by people with haemophilia were processed pharmaceutical products which bore no resemblance to blood transfusion. The infections to those with haemophilia were principally caused by the [[Blood plasma|plasma]] derived product known as [[Factor VIII]], a medicinal product that was sourced from the United States and elsewhere. The creation of such products involved dangerous manufacturing processes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2011/aug/04/bad-blood-cautionary-tale/|title=Bad Blood: A Cautionary Tale|website=Kpbs.org}}</ref> Large groups of paid donors were used (as many as 60,000 per batch, and including prisoners and drug addicts); it only required one infected donor to contaminate an entire batch, which would then infect all of the patients that received that material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemophilia.in/index.php/patient-education/product-safety|title=Hemophilia Federation (India) \u2013 Product Safety|website=Hemophilia.in}}</ref> In contrast, this was at a time when the practice of paying donors for [[whole blood]] in the United States had effectively ceased; the UK did not import whole blood<ref>{{cite web|last1= Glenarthur |first1=Simon|title=Blood: Licensing Requirements|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1983/dec/05/blood-licensing-requirements|website=Hansard|publisher=House of Lords}}</ref> from abroad, but it did import large quantities of Factor VIII given to those infected (as described in the documentary ''[[Factor 8: The Arkansas Prison Blood Scandal]]''). It is said that the principal reason that the UK imported these products was that it did not produce enough of its own.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/19/NHS.medicineandhealth|title=Owen demands inquiry into infected blood scandal|first1=James|last1=Meikle|date=19 August 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1557187/HIV-blood-disaster-papers-were-pulped.html|title=HIV blood disaster papers 'were pulped'|website=Telegraph.co.uk|date=2007-07-11}}</ref>\n\nA study published in 1986 showed that 76% of those who used commercial Factor products became infected with HIV, as opposed to none of those who only used the previous treatment [[cryoprecipitate]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gill |first1=Joan C. |last2=Menitove |first2=Jay E. |last3=Anderson |first3=Philip R. |last4=Casper |first4=James T. |last5=Devare |first5=Sushilkumar G. |last6=Wood |first6=Charles |last7=Adair |first7=Stuart |last8=Casey |first8=James |last9=Scheffel |first9=Christi |last10=Montgomery |first10=Robert R. |title=HTLV-III serology in hemophilia: Relationship with immunologic abnormalities |journal=The Journal of Pediatrics |date=April 1986 |volume=108 |issue=4 |pages=511\u2013516 |doi=10.1016/s0022-3476(86)80824-1 |pmid=3083075 |url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1175&context=virologypub}}</ref>\n\nNo government, healthcare or pharmaceutical entity in the UK has admitted any liability in the scandal, and no [[damages]] or compensation have been paid to those infected or affected, although the government has provided some means-tested benefits to some of the surviving victims through a Trust.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=The Macfarlane Trust| url=http://www.macfarlane.org.uk/|website=Macfarlane.org.uk |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120304164529/http://www.macfarlane.org.uk/ | archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[Haemophilia]] is a mostly [[hereditary|inherited]] [[genetic disorder]] that impairs the body's ability to [[coagulation|clot]], a process needed to [[hemostasis|stop bleeding]].<ref name=NIH2013What>{{cite web|title=What Is Hemophilia?|url=https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/hemophilia|website=NHLBI|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=13 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=CDC2014>{{cite web|title=Hemophilia Facts|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/hemophilia/facts.html|website=CDC|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=26 August 2014}}</ref> This results in people [[bleeding]] longer after an injury, easy [[bruising]], and an increased risk of [[hemarthrosis|bleeding inside joint]]s or other parts of the body.\n\nSome people can now be cured from Haemophilia altogether,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gene therapy used to treat haemophilia|url=https://www.nhs.uk/news/genetics-and-stem-cells/gene-therapy-used-to-treat-haemophilia/|website=nhs.uk|date=2011-12-12}}</ref> but modern \"synthetic\" or \"non-human derived\" Factor products such as Recombinant Factor VIII<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Franchini |first1=M |title=Plasma-derived versus recombinant Factor VIII concentrates for the treatment of haemophilia A: recombinant is better. |journal=Blood Transfusion |date=October 2010 |volume=8 |issue=4 |pages=292\u20136 |doi=10.2450/2010.0067-10 |pmid=20967172 |pmc=2957496 }}</ref> continue to be widely used. Factor products work by replacing the missing Factor proteins, which can take place at home or in hospital. The clotting factors are made either from [[Blood plasma|Plasma]] or by [[Protein production|recombinant methods]]. In the 1970s, haemophiliacs began to be treated with \"Factor Concentrates\", which were sold as a revolutionary treatment. The consequential increase in use led to pharmaceutical companies seeking substantial supplies of plasma, and thousands of donors including prisoners, drug addicts, prostitutes and people known to be infected with HIV or hepatitis were allowed or even paid to give their plasma.\n\nSome of the most famous examples of risky plasma harvesting are those of [[Luckner Cambronne]] who became known as \"The Vampire of the Caribbean\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pepin|first1=Jacques|title=The Origins of AIDS|date=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139501415|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dTaMBrPBK6EC&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=luckner+cambronne+plasma#v=onepage&q=luckner%20cambronne%20plasma&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and also Crysosan Ltd, a company based in [[Canada]] that was found [[Guilt (law)|guilty]] of harvesting plasma from dead Russians bodies and [[relabelling|re-labelling]] it as Swedish.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Ridgeway|first1=James|title=It's All for Sale: The Control of Global Resources|url=https://archive.org/details/itsallforsalecon0000ridg|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/itsallforsalecon0000ridg/page/184 184]|quote=cryosan russian.|publisher=Duke University Press|language=en|date=2004|isbn=978-0822333746}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Arkansas Bloodsuckers: the Clintons, Prisoners and the Blood Trade|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/09/04/arkansas-bloodsuckers-the-clintons-prisoners-and-the-blood-trade/|website=Counterpunch.org|language=en-us|date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Blood money|url=https://www.salon.com/1998/12/24/cov_23news/|website=Salon.com|language=en|date=1998-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nPlasma donations could be collected using a process called [[plasmapheresis]]. In addition to NHS derived Factor produced by [[Bio Products Laboratory]] (BPL), manufacturers that supplied clotting factor products to the UK during the mid-1970s and 1980s included Abbott (Profilate), Armour Pharmaceuticals (Factorate), [[Bayer]]-owned [[Cutter Laboratories|Cutter]] (Koate), [[Baxter International]]-owned Travenol/Hyland (Hemofil/Interhem), Immuno (Kryobulin) and Speywood (Humanate).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taintedblood.info/tb/tlfiles/Brands%20of%20Concentrates%20Used%20in%20UK%20in%201980%20and%201981.pdf |title=Quantities of FVIII Concentrate Used in UK Haemophiliacs: Breakdown by Manufacturer |publisher=Department of Health Freedom of Information release DH_Vol_29_May_1983_Jun_1983 |website=TaintedBlood.info |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= Clinical Trial Certificate |last=Speywood Laboratories Ltd |date = 9 March 1983 |series = BN |file =116 |box=244 |collection = Committee on Safety of Medicines: Sub-Committee on Biological Products |institution =The National Archives (TNA) |location = Kew, London}}</ref>\n\n*BPL: In 2013 the British government sold an 80% stake in the company to [[Bain Capital]] for approximately \u00a3230 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/is-there-no-limit-to-what-this-government-will-privatise-uk-plasma-supplier-sold-to-us-private-8718029.html|title='Is there no limit to what this Government will privatise?': UK plasma|date=18 July 2013|website=Independent.co.uk}}</ref> In 2016 BPL was acquired by the Creat Group for \u00a3820m;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/news/q/date/2016/05/19/press-release-creat-group-corporation-agrees-to-acquire-bio-products-laboratory-ltd/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Creat Group Corporation agrees to acquire Bio Products Laboratory Ltd. - Bio Products Laboratory Ltd.|website=Bpl.co.uk|access-date=8 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109030610/http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/news/q/date/2016/05/19/press-release-creat-group-corporation-agrees-to-acquire-bio-products-laboratory-ltd/|archive-date=9 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> the government stood to receive \u00a3164m from its remaining 20% share in BPL.\n*Armour '''(Revlon)''': In 1978 Armour was purchased by [[Revlon]] for $90m<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/07/06/archives/revlon-set-to-buy-armour-drug-units.html|title=Revlon Set to Buy Armour Druz Units|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> which owned the company until 1987 when it was sold to [[Rh\u00f4ne-Poulenc]] which purchased Revlon's drug operation for $690m in cash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/30/business/rorer-buys-drug-unit-of-revlon.html|title=RORER BUYS DRUG UNIT OF REVLON|date=30 November 1985|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|last1=Crudele|first1=John}}</ref> In 1996 Armour and Behringwerke were merged and became Centeon. In 1999 Centeon changed its name to Aventis Behring after the parent companies, Rorer and [[Hoechst AG]] merged to become Aventis. In 2004, CSL completed its acquisition of Aventis Behring for $925m, today known as [[CSL Behring]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cslbehring.com/about/heritage-history.htm|title=Saving Lives For More Than A Century \u2013 CSL Behring|website=Cslbehring.com}}</ref>\n*Bayer: Cutter Labs, which produced Factor VIII, was originally owned by [[Miles Laboratories]]. In 1974 Cutter Labs was purchased by Bayer, and in 1978 Bayer also purchased Miles Labs. In 1995 Bayer dropped the Miles Labs brand name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bayer.com/en/1988-2001.aspx|title=1988-2001 \u2013 A Journey through the History of Bayer|website=Bayer.com}}</ref> In 2005 a new company, Talecris<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050401005264/en/Announcing-Launch-Talecris-Biotherapeutics-Combining-Proud-History|title=Announcing the Launch of Talecris Biotherapeutics: Combining a Proud History of Patient Care with a Bold New Vision|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|date=April 2005}}</ref> (set up by [[Cerberus Capital Management]] and Ampersand)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ampersandcapital.com/|title=Ampersand|website=Ampersandcapital.com}}</ref> acquired Bayer's plasma business and assets for $590m. Bayer however, did not include its recombinant Factor VIII \"Kogenate\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kogenatefs.com/|title=Kogenate\u00ae FS, Antihemophilic Factor (Recombinant)|website=Kogenatefs.com}}</ref> in the sale and remains active in distribution internationally. In 2009, [[CSL Limited]] attempted to takeover Talecris for $3.1 billion but was stopped by the [[Federal Trade Commission]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2009/05/ftc-authorizes-suit-stop-csls-proposed-31-billion-acquisition|title=FTC Authorizes Suit To Stop CSLs Proposed $3.1 Billion Acquisition of Talecris Biotherapeutics \u2013 Federal Trade Commission|website=Ftc.gov|date=2009-05-27}}</ref> which charged the deal would be illegal. In 2011, a year after announcing the $4bn deal, [[Grifols]] completed a takeover of Talecris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grifols.com/en/web/international/investor-relations/acquisition-of-talecris|title=Grifols Worldwide :: Acquisition of Talecris|website=Grifols.com}}</ref>\n*Hyland/Travenol '''(Baxter)''': Baxter created Travenol Labs in 1949 and acquired Hyland Labs in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/baxter-international-inc-history/|title=History of Baxter International Inc. |website=FundingUniverse.com}}</ref> In 1993 Baxter was implicated in a lawsuit brought by haemophiliacs infected with HIV in the United States,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/04/us/aids-suit-accuses-companies-of-selling-bad-blood-products.html|title=AIDS Suit Accuses Companies of Selling Bad Blood Products|date=4 October 1993|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> and by the end of that year president James Tobin quit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/tobin-resigns-from-baxter|title=TOBIN RESIGNS FROM BAXTER \u2013 Pharmaceutical industry news|website=Thepharmaletter.com}}</ref> In 1996 Baxter settled a lawsuit brought by haemophiliacs in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-04/business/fi-42879_1_blood-products|title=Baxter Is in Talks to Settle Tainted-Blood Suit in Japan|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=MAGGIE|last=FARLEY|date=4 March 1996}}</ref> In 2015, Baxter split-off its haemophilia sector to create [[Baxalta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/baxalta-spins-off-from-baxter/81251456|title=Baxalta Spins Off from Baxter|website=Genengnews.com}}</ref> In 2016 Baxalta was acquired by [[Shire (pharmaceutical company)|Shire plc]] for $32bn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/shire-baxalta-complete-32b-merger/81252788|title=Shire, Baxalta Complete $32B Merger|website=Genengnews.com}}</ref>\n*Immuno AG: Baxter purchased Immuno AG in 1996 in an effort to keep up with competitors for some $715m.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB841282001213737000|title=Baxter Will Acquire Immuno In Deal Valued at $715 Million|first1=Steven|last1=Lipin|first2=Thomas M. Burton Staff Reporters of The Wall Street|last2=Journal|date=29 August 1996|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/30/business/baxter-purchasing-immuno-swiss-blood-products-maker.html|title=Baxter Purchasing Immuno, Swiss Blood-Products Maker|date=30 August 1996|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|last1=Freudenheim|first1=Milt}}</ref>\n\n== 1973 - 1986 - Hepatitis ==\nThe dangers of factor concentrates had been raised since their inception. In 1974, American scientist [[Judith Graham Pool]] (who previously discovered the frozen blood product [[cryoprecipitate]], a safer treatment) described the products as \"dangerous\" and \"unethical\" and warned against their use. The [[World Health Organization]] also warned the UK not to import blood from countries with a high prevalence of hepatitis, such as the United States.<ref name=PE1449>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=28 July 2017 |title=Justice delayed |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd }}</ref>\n\nIn May 1975, the World Health Organization passed a widely circulated resolution urging all countries to aim at self-sufficiency in blood-products.\n\nIn September 1975, an article was published detailing occurrences of a new kind of Hepatitis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/337714 |title=Hepatitis Types B and Non-B, Epidemiologic Background|website=jamanetwork.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1975 an episode of the ''[[World in Action]]'' programme highlighted the danger of Hepatitis from imported Factor products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/PEN0131400.PDF |title=World in Action - \"Blood Money\"|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 1978 more than 50% of the Factor VIII used in England was being imported from overseas. This was because the country had failed to become self-sufficient in its own supplies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=P |title=Factor VIII supply and demand. |journal=BMJ |date=21 June 1980 |volume=280 |issue=6230 |pages=1531\u20131532 |doi=10.1136/bmj.280.6230.1531 |pmid=6770954 |pmc=1601689 }}</ref>\n\nThe BPL,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/|title=About BPL \u2013 Bio Products Laboratory Ltd.|website=Bpl.co.uk|access-date=13 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029184734/http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/|archive-date=29 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> which manufactured UK blood products, ran into continual trouble from under-funding. The Archer Report said, \"In July 1979, the Medicines Inspectorate visited BPL. They reported that the buildings were never designed for the scale of production envisaged. They commented: 'If this were a commercial operation we would have no hesitation in recommending that manufacture should cease until the facility was upgraded to a minimum acceptable level'. BPL was rescued by Crown Immunity. Among their recommendations the Inspectorate advised: 'Under no circumstances should production of any product be increased under the existing manufacturing conditions'. Meanwhile, the existing plant continued production, relying on Crown Immunity to dispense with all the requirements of the Medicines Act, but was able to meet only about 40% of the national requirements.\"\n\nA study published in December 1983 showed conclusively that the risk to a haemophiliac of contracting Hepatitis C by using untreated Factor products was 100% upon first exposure.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fletcher |first1=M L |last2=Trowell |first2=J M |last3=Craske |first3=J |last4=Pavier |first4=K |last5=Rizza |first5=C R |title=Non-A non-B hepatitis after transfusion of factor VIII in infrequently treated patients. |journal=BMJ |date=10 December 1983 |volume=287 |issue=6407 |pages=1754\u20131757 |doi=10.1136/bmj.287.6407.1754 |pmid=6416577 |pmc=1549875 }}</ref>\n\n== 1981 - 1986 - HIV ==\nIn July 1982, the American [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) reported that at least 3 haemophiliacs there had developed Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, 2 had died, and all 3 had used untreated Factor products.<ref>{{cite web |title=1982- AIDS is Discovered Among Hemophilia Patients |url=http://www.hemophiliafed.org/news-stories/2014/03/aids_and_hemophilia/ |website=Hemophilia Federation of America |date=17 March 2014}}</ref> The CDC said that \"the occurrence among the three hemophiliac cases suggests the possible transmission of an agent through blood products\".\n\nIn March 1983, the CDC reported that \"Blood products or blood appear responsible for AIDS among hemophilia patients\".<ref>{{cite web |title=1983\u2014CDC Determines that AIDS is Spread Through Infected Blood - Hemophilia Federation of America |url=http://www.hemophiliafed.org/news-stories/2014/03/1984-cdc-determines-that-aids-is-spreading-through-infected-blood/ |website=Hemophilia Federation of America |date=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1983 Dr N. S. Galbraith, director of the Communicable Disease Surveillance Centre in England and Wales, sent a paper entitled \"Action on AIDS\" to Dr Ian Field at the [[Department of Health and Social Security]] in London informing him of the death from AIDS of a haemophiliac who had received Factor VIII concentrate imported from the United States. Galbraith stated: \"I have reviewed the literature and come to the conclusion that all blood products made from blood donated in the USA after 1978 should be withdrawn from use until the risk of AIDS transmission by these products has been clarified ... I am most surprised that the USA manufacturers of the implicated blood products have not informed their customers of this new hazard. I assume no critical warning has been received in the United Kingdom?\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Preliminary Report Chapter 8: HIV and AIDS|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/preliminary-report/chapter-8/#footnote-10795-30-backlink|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk|language=en}}</ref> Despite Galbraith's warning the products were not withdrawn: a Department of Health letter considered that his suggestion was \"premature\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/preliminary-report/chapter-8/|title=Preliminary Report Chapter 8: HIV and AIDS|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1983 a leaflet distributed to UK blood donors answered the question as to whether AIDS could be transmitted by blood-products to be \"Almost certainly yes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/SGH0026675.PDF|title=Brochure : Aids and how it concerns blood donors|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1983 the UK Health Minister, Ken Clarke told parliament that \"There is no conclusive evidence that AIDS is transmitted by blood products\" and the importation of infected products continued. When giving evidence to the Penrose Inquiry, Dr Mark Winter said that at the time Ken Clarke made this statement \"all haemophilia clinicians by this stage clearly believed that commercial blood products could and were transmitting AIDS\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Report: Chapter 9 - Knowledge of the Geographical Spread and Prevalence of HIV/AIDS 1 |url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/text/354876_chapter_9.html#footnote-042-backlink |website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1984, Lord Glenarthur (Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the DHSS) said that \"It remains the case that there is no conclusive evidence of the transmission of AIDS through blood products, although the circumstantial evidence is strong\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/SGH0076160.PDF|title=Letter to Government|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> and again the use of untreated Factor products and importation continued.\n\n== 2000 - Destroyed Evidence Investigation ==\nIn April 2000 the Department of Health published an internal audit to examine the loss of records relating to Hepatitis C litigation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flint|first1=Caroline|title=Destroyed Documents (Blood Products)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060523/text/60523w0029.htm|website=Hansard|publisher=House of Commons}}</ref> The report concluded that \"an arbitrary and unjustified decision, most likely taken by an inexperienced member of staff, was responsible for the destruction of a series of files containing the minutes and background papers of the Advisory Committee on the Virological Safety of Blood (ACSVB)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58a18aeb2e69cf7248eeddbc/t/5b1a74a9352f53bcbf9a4c8c/1528460512936/DH+Audit+on+GEB.pdf|title=Internal Audit Review - Hepatitis C Litigation - Final Report|date=April 2000|website=Squarespace.com|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== 2009 \u2013 The Archer Report ==\nIn the early 2000s the former Solicitor General for England and Wales, [[Peter Archer, Baron Archer of Sandwell|Lord Archer]], campaigned for an inquiry into the tainted blood scandal alongside [[David Owen|Lord Owen]], who was the Health Minister from 1974 to 1976, [[Patrick Jenkin, Baron Jenkin of Roding|Lord Jenkin]], former Shadow Health Secretary, and others. They were unsuccessful.\n\nIn a 1990 episode of ''[[The Cook Report]]'', Owen said: \"I can see why some people would be unhappy with having all the facts revealed because it will show negligence\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cook Report \u2013 Profits Before Patients|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jb1Kb-WvW2o|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> In September 2016 Owen gave a speech in London during which he said the scandal had been covered-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uqt0xXz-saw|title=Lord David Owen \u2013 Bad Blood Speech 29/9/16|date=30 September 2016|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nArcher chaired a privately funded independent investigation set up in 2007. The Archer Report was published in 2009 and aimed to uncover the causes of the events that led to the thousands of infections and deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/delays-led-to-thousands-receiving-contaminated-blood-1629555.html|title=Delays Led to Thousands Receiving Contaminated Blood|author=Sam Marsden|website=Independent.co.uk|date=23 February 2009|accessdate=14 February 2010}}</ref> The report held no legal or official status and was unable to subpoena witnesses or demand the disclosure of documents.<ref name=PE1449/> Nonetheless, it sought to address the issue of missing evidence and documents relating to the scandal. For example, the ministerial papers of Lord Owen had been destroyed. \"We have been unable to ascertain who carried out the destruction of the papers, and who gave the instructions. But the conclusion appears inescapable that some official made a decision which he or she had no authority to make, or that someone was guilty of a serious error of judgement. The consequence is that Lord Owen has done his best to recollect details of events a quarter of a century ago, but both he, and we, have been deprived of the primary sources\", Archer reported. Lord Jenkin also voiced his difficulties obtaining documents for the inquiry, although the report stated: \"He subsequently received from the Department two bundles of documents. One of these was to be treated as confidential\". Lord Jenkin felt that the destruction of records was deliberate, and done \"in order to draw a line under the disaster\".<ref name=\"Archer Report\">{{Cite book |title=The Archer Inquiry |year=2009 |quote=On 13 April 2005 Lord Jenkin met Sir Nigel, who apologised for the original reply. Lord Jenkin was left with the clear impression from their subsequent conversation that all the files bearing upon the issue of contaminated blood products had been destroyed, and that this had been done 'with intent, in order to draw a line under the disaster'. |url=http://www.archercbbp.com/files/report/76_Lord%20Archer%20Report.DOC |access-date=1 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703132440/http://www.archercbbp.com/files/report/76_Lord%20Archer%20Report.DOC |archive-date=3 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAnother handling error is described in the inquiry: \"mishandling of documents arose in connection with a number of files relating to the Advisory Committee on the Virological Safety of Blood between May 1989 and February 1992 which were found to be missing\". The report went on to state: \"They were in fact destroyed over a period from July 1994 to March 1998\". When summarising these events it is stated \"some of those who gave evidence to us suspected that there was an exercise in suppressing evidence of negligence or misconduct.\"\n\n== 2015 \u2013 Scottish Penrose Inquiry ==\n{{Main|Penrose Inquiry}}\nIn 2008 the Scottish government announced [[Penrose Inquiry|a public inquiry]] into the scandal covering Scotland only, to be chaired by [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose|Lord Penrose]]. The inquiry's terms of reference outlined five deaths that were to be examined, but only one of those victims was a haemophiliac and that person had been infected with hepatitis C in the 1960s, before the factor concentrates were introduced.\n\nPublished in 2015, the inquiry was described as a [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] and waste of public money (over \u00a312 million) by critics after it made just one recommendation and failed to apportion any blame in the scandal. Its recommendation was to offer blood tests to anyone in Scotland who had a blood transfusion before 1991 and who had not already been tested for hepatitis C.\n\n== 2017 \u2013 Legal action and UK public inquiry ==\nIn July 2017 a group legal action ''Jason Evans & Ors'' was brought against the government on behalf of more than 500 people by Collins Solicitors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Momentum in Contaminated Blood Scandal grows as Collins apply for a Group Litigation Order \u2013 Collins Solicitors Press Release dated 4 July 2017|url=http://www.collinslaw.co.uk/post.php?s=2017-07-04-momentum-in-contaminated-blood-scandal-grows-as-collins-apply-for-a-group-litigation-order-collins-solicitors-press-release-dated-4-july-2017|website=Collinslaw.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ITV News \u2013 Families seek justice in Blood Scandal \u2013 4th July 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vCLXW4Mm5o|date=4 July 2017|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> After years of increasing pressure from campaigners and [[Member of parliament|MP]]s, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced a full UK-wide public inquiry into the scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Peter|last2=Topping|first2=Alexandra|title=Theresa May orders contaminated blood scandal inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/11/contaminated-blood-scandal-theresa-may-orders-inquiry|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-40601013|title=Blood probe 'lessons must be learned'|work=BBC News|date=14 July 2017|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> In September 2017 a court ruling found in favour of the victims allowing them to launch a [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] action to seek damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41406105|title=Victims win contaminated blood ruling|date=26 September 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/victims-and-families-can-bring-high-court-action-on-contaminated-blood-products/|title=Victims and families can bring High Court action on contaminated blood products|date=26 September 2017|work=Evening Express|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926200244/https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/victims-and-families-can-bring-high-court-action-on-contaminated-blood-products/|archive-date=26 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-26/victims-and-families-win-high-court-ruling-to-seek-damages-over-contaminated-blood-products/|title=Victims and families win High Court ruling to seek damages over contaminated blood products|work=ITV News|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== 2018 \u2013 False ministerial statements withdrawn ==\nIn June 2018 the Department of Health issued an apology, because for two years Ministers had told Parliament that in relation to Contaminated Blood Scandal evidence: \"All documents up to 1995 are available through the National Archive\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Blood: Contamination:Written question \u2013 65851 |url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-27/65851/ |website=UK Parliament |language=English}}</ref>\n\n== 2019 \u2013 Files still missing ==\nIn February 2019, it emerged that around 450 files had been taken from the archives by staff from the Department of Health and Social Security, and not returned, sparking concerns among campaigners that the department was attempting a cover-up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/contaminated-blood-scandal-documents-nhs-hiv-hepatitis-haemophilia-factor-8-cover-up-a8773716.html|title=Cover-up fears as hundreds of contaminated blood files 'vanish' before inquiry can see them|date=11 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government support ==\nSuccessive governments, both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], have been criticised for their handling of the case, limited support schemes and refusal to conduct a public inquiry (until 2017). Some limited support has been provided to selected individuals through [[charitable trust]]s<ref name=\"auto\"/> which is often subject to [[means test]]ing, though no damages or compensation have ever been paid to UK victims or their families.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harpin|first1=Lee|title=Victims of contaminated blood scandal weren't given Tory compensation|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/victims-contaminated-blood-scandal-werent-10854692|website=mirror|date=22 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In the urgent question on 16...: 21 Jan 2016: House of Commons debates - TheyWorkForYou|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2016-01-21b.1583.1|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 the Conservative government made \u00a342 million available to those affected by HIV,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2014-10-20/211081/|title=Blood: Contamination: Written question \u2013 211081|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> this equates to around \u00a329,000 on average between the 1,437 people who received a payment.\n\nIn 2017 the Conservatives announced more funds for those with first-stage chronic hepatitis C, but this additional money was reportedly to be sourced from funds for other tainted blood victims. The Department of Health was accused of robbing one set of victims to pay another. Officials stated that it had made available an extra \u00a3125 million, more than any previous government, but critics said this money was simply accounted for as a cost to the NHS of extending treatments to hepatitis C sufferers sooner.<ref name=PE1440>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=24 March 2017 |title=What a Hunt |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[HIV trial in Libya]] after over 400 children were infected with HIV at Libyan Children's Hospital.\n* [[Contaminated blood]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Contaminated haemophilia blood products|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=October 2018}}\n{{short description|Scandal in the United Kingdom about contaminated blood Red}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox event \n| title                    = Contaminated Blood Scandal HIV\n| image                    = Bottles of factor viii haemophilia treatment.jpg\n| caption                  = Bottle of Factor VIII, a product used to treat haemophilia\n| date                     = 1970s & 1980s\n| place                    = [[United Kingdom]]\n| cause                    = Contaminated Factor VIII & Factor IX\n| reported death(s)        = 1,246+\n| inquiries                = [[Contaminated blood scandal inquiry|Contaminated Blood Scandal Inquiry]]\n| suspects                 =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n}}\nThe '''Contaminated Blood Scandal''' in the United Kingdom arose when at least 3,891 people, most of whom suffered from [[haemophilia]], became infected with [[hepatitis C]] of whom 1,243 were also infected with [[HIV]], the virus that leads to [[HIV/AIDS|acquired immune deficiency syndrome]] (AIDS), as a result of receiving [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products|contaminated clotting factor products]] supplied by the [[National Health Service]] (NHS) in the 1970s and 1980s. As of October 2017 there were at least 1,246 confirmed deaths in the UK of people who were killed by the clotting agents Factor VIII & Factor IX and the viruses they transmitted. Some have estimated that the total number of those who have died could be as high as 2,400 though exact figures are not known.\n\nDuring the 1970s and 1980s, some people were infected with Hepatitis C via blood transfusions under entirely different circumstances. However, the Factor Concentrate products used by people with haemophilia were processed pharmaceutical products which bore no resemblance to blood transfusion. The infections to those with haemophilia were principally caused by the [[Blood plasma|plasma]] derived product known as [[Factor VIII]], a medicinal product that was sourced from the United States and elsewhere. The creation of such products involved dangerous manufacturing processes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2011/aug/04/bad-blood-cautionary-tale/|title=Bad Blood: A Cautionary Tale|website=Kpbs.org}}</ref> Large groups of paid donors were used (as many as 60,000 per batch, and including prisoners and drug addicts); it only required one infected donor to contaminate an entire batch, which would then infect all of the patients that received that material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemophilia.in/index.php/patient-education/product-safety|title=Hemophilia Federation (India) \u2013 Product Safety|website=Hemophilia.in}}</ref> In contrast, this was at a time when the practice of paying donors for [[whole blood]] in the United States had effectively ceased; the UK did not import whole blood<ref>{{cite web|last1= Glenarthur |first1=Simon|title=Blood: Licensing Requirements|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1983/dec/05/blood-licensing-requirements|website=Hansard|publisher=House of Lords}}</ref> from abroad, but it did import large quantities of Factor VIII given to those infected (as described in the documentary ''[[Factor 8: The Arkansas Prison Blood Scandal]]''). It is said that the principal reason that the UK imported these products was that it did not produce enough of its own.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/19/NHS.medicineandhealth|title=Owen demands inquiry into infected blood scandal|first1=James|last1=Meikle|date=19 August 2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1557187/HIV-blood-disaster-papers-were-pulped.html|title=HIV blood disaster papers 'were pulped'|website=Telegraph.co.uk|date=2007-07-11}}</ref>\n\nA study published in 1986 showed that 76% of those who used commercial Factor products became infected with HIV, as opposed to none of those who only used the previous treatment [[cryoprecipitate]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gill |first1=Joan C. |last2=Menitove |first2=Jay E. |last3=Anderson |first3=Philip R. |last4=Casper |first4=James T. |last5=Devare |first5=Sushilkumar G. |last6=Wood |first6=Charles |last7=Adair |first7=Stuart |last8=Casey |first8=James |last9=Scheffel |first9=Christi |last10=Montgomery |first10=Robert R. |title=HTLV-III serology in hemophilia: Relationship with immunologic abnormalities |journal=The Journal of Pediatrics |date=April 1986 |volume=108 |issue=4 |pages=511\u2013516 |doi=10.1016/s0022-3476(86)80824-1 |pmid=3083075 |url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1175&context=virologypub}}</ref>\n\nNo government, healthcare or pharmaceutical entity in the UK has admitted any liability in the scandal, and no [[damages]] or compensation have been paid to those infected or affected, although the government has provided some means-tested benefits to some of the surviving victims through a Trust.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=The Macfarlane Trust| url=http://www.macfarlane.org.uk/|website=Macfarlane.org.uk |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120304164529/http://www.macfarlane.org.uk/ | archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[Haemophilia]] is a mostly [[hereditary|inherited]] [[genetic disorder]] that impairs the body's ability to [[coagulation|clot]], a process needed to [[hemostasis|stop bleeding]].<ref name=NIH2013What>{{cite web|title=What Is Hemophilia?|url=https://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/health-topics/topics/hemophilia|website=NHLBI|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=13 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=CDC2014>{{cite web|title=Hemophilia Facts|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/hemophilia/facts.html|website=CDC|accessdate=8 September 2016|date=26 August 2014}}</ref> This results in people [[bleeding]] longer after an injury, easy [[bruising]], and an increased risk of [[hemarthrosis|bleeding inside joint]]s or other parts of the body.\n\nSome people can now be cured from Haemophilia altogether,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gene therapy used to treat haemophilia|url=https://www.nhs.uk/news/genetics-and-stem-cells/gene-therapy-used-to-treat-haemophilia/|website=nhs.uk|date=2011-12-12}}</ref> but modern \"synthetic\" or \"non-human derived\" Factor products such as Recombinant Factor VIII<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Franchini |first1=M |title=Plasma-derived versus recombinant Factor VIII concentrates for the treatment of haemophilia A: recombinant is better. |journal=Blood Transfusion |date=October 2010 |volume=8 |issue=4 |pages=292\u20136 |doi=10.2450/2010.0067-10 |pmid=20967172 |pmc=2957496 }}</ref> continue to be widely used. Factor products work by replacing the missing Factor proteins, which can take place at home or in hospital. The clotting factors are made either from [[Blood plasma|Plasma]] or by [[Protein production|recombinant methods]]. In the 1970s, haemophiliacs began to be treated with \"Factor Concentrates\", which were sold as a revolutionary treatment. The consequential increase in use led to pharmaceutical companies seeking substantial supplies of plasma, and thousands of donors including prisoners, drug addicts, prostitutes and people known to be infected with HIV or hepatitis were allowed or even paid to give their plasma.\n\nSome of the most famous examples of risky plasma harvesting are those of [[Luckner Cambronne]] who became known as \"The Vampire of the Caribbean\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pepin|first1=Jacques|title=The Origins of AIDS|date=2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139501415|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dTaMBrPBK6EC&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=luckner+cambronne+plasma#v=onepage&q=luckner%20cambronne%20plasma&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and also Crysosan Ltd, a company based in [[Canada]] that was found [[Guilt (law)|guilty]] of harvesting plasma from dead Russians bodies and [[relabelling|re-labelling]] it as Swedish.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Ridgeway|first1=James|title=It's All for Sale: The Control of Global Resources|url=https://archive.org/details/itsallforsalecon0000ridg|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/itsallforsalecon0000ridg/page/184 184]|quote=cryosan russian.|publisher=Duke University Press|language=en|date=2004|isbn=978-0822333746}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Arkansas Bloodsuckers: the Clintons, Prisoners and the Blood Trade|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2015/09/04/arkansas-bloodsuckers-the-clintons-prisoners-and-the-blood-trade/|website=Counterpunch.org|language=en-us|date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Blood money|url=https://www.salon.com/1998/12/24/cov_23news/|website=Salon.com|language=en|date=1998-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nPlasma donations could be collected using a process called [[plasmapheresis]]. In addition to NHS derived Factor produced by [[Bio Products Laboratory]] (BPL), manufacturers that supplied clotting factor products to the UK during the mid-1970s and 1980s included Abbott (Profilate), Armour Pharmaceuticals (Factorate), [[Bayer]]-owned [[Cutter Laboratories|Cutter]] (Koate), [[Baxter International]]-owned Travenol/Hyland (Hemofil/Interhem), Immuno (Kryobulin) and Speywood (Humanate).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taintedblood.info/tb/tlfiles/Brands%20of%20Concentrates%20Used%20in%20UK%20in%201980%20and%201981.pdf |title=Quantities of FVIII Concentrate Used in UK Haemophiliacs: Breakdown by Manufacturer |publisher=Department of Health Freedom of Information release DH_Vol_29_May_1983_Jun_1983 |website=TaintedBlood.info |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*BPL: In 2013 the British government sold an 80% stake in the company to [[Bain Capital]] for approximately \u00a3230 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/is-there-no-limit-to-what-this-government-will-privatise-uk-plasma-supplier-sold-to-us-private-8718029.html|title='Is there no limit to what this Government will privatise?': UK plasma|date=18 July 2013|website=Independent.co.uk}}</ref> In 2016 BPL was acquired by the Creat Group for \u00a3820m;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/news/q/date/2016/05/19/press-release-creat-group-corporation-agrees-to-acquire-bio-products-laboratory-ltd/|title=PRESS RELEASE: Creat Group Corporation agrees to acquire Bio Products Laboratory Ltd. - Bio Products Laboratory Ltd.|website=Bpl.co.uk|access-date=8 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109030610/http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/news/q/date/2016/05/19/press-release-creat-group-corporation-agrees-to-acquire-bio-products-laboratory-ltd/|archive-date=9 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> the government stood to receive \u00a3164m from its remaining 20% share in BPL.\n*Armour '''(Revlon)''': In 1978 Armour was purchased by [[Revlon]] for $90m<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/07/06/archives/revlon-set-to-buy-armour-drug-units.html|title=Revlon Set to Buy Armour Druz Units|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> which owned the company until 1987 when it was sold to [[Rh\u00f4ne-Poulenc]] which purchased Revlon's drug operation for $690m in cash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/30/business/rorer-buys-drug-unit-of-revlon.html|title=RORER BUYS DRUG UNIT OF REVLON|date=30 November 1985|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|last1=Crudele|first1=John}}</ref> In 1996 Armour and Behringwerke were merged and became Centeon. In 1999 Centeon changed its name to Aventis Behring after the parent companies, Rorer and [[Hoechst AG]] merged to become Aventis. In 2004, CSL completed its acquisition of Aventis Behring for $925m, today known as [[CSL Behring]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cslbehring.com/about/heritage-history.htm|title=Saving Lives For More Than A Century \u2013 CSL Behring|website=Cslbehring.com}}</ref>\n*Bayer: Cutter Labs, which produced Factor VIII, was originally owned by [[Miles Laboratories]]. In 1974 Cutter Labs was purchased by Bayer, and in 1978 Bayer also purchased Miles Labs. In 1995 Bayer dropped the Miles Labs brand name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bayer.com/en/1988-2001.aspx|title=1988-2001 \u2013 A Journey through the History of Bayer|website=Bayer.com}}</ref> In 2005 a new company, Talecris<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050401005264/en/Announcing-Launch-Talecris-Biotherapeutics-Combining-Proud-History|title=Announcing the Launch of Talecris Biotherapeutics: Combining a Proud History of Patient Care with a Bold New Vision|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|date=April 2005}}</ref> (set up by [[Cerberus Capital Management]] and Ampersand)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ampersandcapital.com/|title=Ampersand|website=Ampersandcapital.com}}</ref> acquired Bayer's plasma business and assets for $590m. Bayer however, did not include its recombinant Factor VIII \"Kogenate\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kogenatefs.com/|title=Kogenate\u00ae FS, Antihemophilic Factor (Recombinant)|website=Kogenatefs.com}}</ref> in the sale and remains active in distribution internationally. In 2009, [[CSL Limited]] attempted to takeover Talecris for $3.1 billion but was stopped by the [[Federal Trade Commission]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2009/05/ftc-authorizes-suit-stop-csls-proposed-31-billion-acquisition|title=FTC Authorizes Suit To Stop CSLs Proposed $3.1 Billion Acquisition of Talecris Biotherapeutics \u2013 Federal Trade Commission|website=Ftc.gov|date=2009-05-27}}</ref> which charged the deal would be illegal. In 2011, a year after announcing the $4bn deal, [[Grifols]] completed a takeover of Talecris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grifols.com/en/web/international/investor-relations/acquisition-of-talecris|title=Grifols Worldwide :: Acquisition of Talecris|website=Grifols.com}}</ref>\n*Hyland/Travenol '''(Baxter)''': Baxter created Travenol Labs in 1949 and acquired Hyland Labs in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/baxter-international-inc-history/|title=History of Baxter International Inc. |website=FundingUniverse.com}}</ref> In 1993 Baxter was implicated in a lawsuit brought by haemophiliacs infected with HIV in the United States,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/04/us/aids-suit-accuses-companies-of-selling-bad-blood-products.html|title=AIDS Suit Accuses Companies of Selling Bad Blood Products|date=4 October 1993|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> and by the end of that year president James Tobin quit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepharmaletter.com/article/tobin-resigns-from-baxter|title=TOBIN RESIGNS FROM BAXTER \u2013 Pharmaceutical industry news|website=Thepharmaletter.com}}</ref> In 1996 Baxter settled a lawsuit brought by haemophiliacs in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-04/business/fi-42879_1_blood-products|title=Baxter Is in Talks to Settle Tainted-Blood Suit in Japan|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=MAGGIE|last=FARLEY|date=4 March 1996}}</ref> In 2015, Baxter split-off its haemophilia sector to create [[Baxalta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/baxalta-spins-off-from-baxter/81251456|title=Baxalta Spins Off from Baxter|website=Genengnews.com}}</ref> In 2016 Baxalta was acquired by [[Shire (pharmaceutical company)|Shire plc]] for $32bn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genengnews.com/gen-news-highlights/shire-baxalta-complete-32b-merger/81252788|title=Shire, Baxalta Complete $32B Merger|website=Genengnews.com}}</ref>\n*Immuno AG: Baxter purchased Immuno AG in 1996 in an effort to keep up with competitors for some $715m.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB841282001213737000|title=Baxter Will Acquire Immuno In Deal Valued at $715 Million|first1=Steven|last1=Lipin|first2=Thomas M. Burton Staff Reporters of The Wall Street|last2=Journal|date=29 August 1996|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/30/business/baxter-purchasing-immuno-swiss-blood-products-maker.html|title=Baxter Purchasing Immuno, Swiss Blood-Products Maker|date=30 August 1996|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|last1=Freudenheim|first1=Milt}}</ref>\n\n== 1973 - 1986 - Hepatitis ==\nThe dangers of factor concentrates had been raised since their inception. In 1974, American scientist [[Judith Graham Pool]] (who previously discovered the frozen blood product [[cryoprecipitate]], a safer treatment) described the products as \"dangerous\" and \"unethical\" and warned against their use. The [[World Health Organization]] also warned the UK not to import blood from countries with a high prevalence of hepatitis, such as the United States.<ref name=PE1449>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=28 July 2017 |title=Justice delayed |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd }}</ref>\n\nIn May 1975, the World Health Organization passed a widely circulated resolution urging all countries to aim at self-sufficiency in blood-products.\n\nIn September 1975, an article was published detailing occurrences of a new kind of Hepatitis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/337714 |title=Hepatitis Types B and Non-B, Epidemiologic Background|website=jamanetwork.com}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1975 an episode of the ''[[World in Action]]'' programme highlighted the danger of Hepatitis from imported Factor products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/PEN0131400.PDF |title=World in Action - \"Blood Money\"|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 1978 more than 50% of the Factor VIII used in England was being imported from overseas. This was because the country had failed to become self-sufficient in its own supplies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=P |title=Factor VIII supply and demand. |journal=BMJ |date=21 June 1980 |volume=280 |issue=6230 |pages=1531\u20131532 |doi=10.1136/bmj.280.6230.1531 |pmid=6770954 |pmc=1601689 }}</ref>\n\nThe BPL,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/|title=About BPL \u2013 Bio Products Laboratory Ltd.|website=Bpl.co.uk|access-date=13 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029184734/http://www.bpl.co.uk/about-bpl/|archive-date=29 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> which manufactured UK blood products, ran into continual trouble from under-funding. The Archer Report said, \"In July 1979, the Medicines Inspectorate visited BPL. They reported that the buildings were never designed for the scale of production envisaged. They commented: 'If this were a commercial operation we would have no hesitation in recommending that manufacture should cease until the facility was upgraded to a minimum acceptable level'. BPL was rescued by Crown Immunity. Among their recommendations the Inspectorate advised: 'Under no circumstances should production of any product be increased under the existing manufacturing conditions'. Meanwhile, the existing plant continued production, relying on Crown Immunity to dispense with all the requirements of the Medicines Act, but was able to meet only about 40% of the national requirements.\"\n\nA study published in December 1983 showed conclusively that the risk to a haemophiliac of contracting Hepatitis C by using untreated Factor products was 100% upon first exposure.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fletcher |first1=M L |last2=Trowell |first2=J M |last3=Craske |first3=J |last4=Pavier |first4=K |last5=Rizza |first5=C R |title=Non-A non-B hepatitis after transfusion of factor VIII in infrequently treated patients. |journal=BMJ |date=10 December 1983 |volume=287 |issue=6407 |pages=1754\u20131757 |doi=10.1136/bmj.287.6407.1754 |pmid=6416577 |pmc=1549875 }}</ref>\n\n== 1981 - 1986 - HIV ==\nIn July 1982, the American [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) reported that at least 3 haemophiliacs there had developed Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, 2 had died, and all 3 had used untreated Factor products.<ref>{{cite web |title=1982- AIDS is Discovered Among Hemophilia Patients |url=http://www.hemophiliafed.org/news-stories/2014/03/aids_and_hemophilia/ |website=Hemophilia Federation of America |date=17 March 2014}}</ref> The CDC said that \"the occurrence among the three hemophiliac cases suggests the possible transmission of an agent through blood products\".\n\nIn March 1983, the CDC reported that \"Blood products or blood appear responsible for AIDS among hemophilia patients\".<ref>{{cite web |title=1983\u2014CDC Determines that AIDS is Spread Through Infected Blood - Hemophilia Federation of America |url=http://www.hemophiliafed.org/news-stories/2014/03/1984-cdc-determines-that-aids-is-spreading-through-infected-blood/ |website=Hemophilia Federation of America |date=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1983 Dr N. S. Galbraith, director of the Communicable Disease Surveillance Centre in England and Wales, sent a paper entitled \"Action on AIDS\" to Dr Ian Field at the [[Department of Health and Social Security]] in London informing him of the death from AIDS of a haemophiliac who had received Factor VIII concentrate imported from the United States. Galbraith stated: \"I have reviewed the literature and come to the conclusion that all blood products made from blood donated in the USA after 1978 should be withdrawn from use until the risk of AIDS transmission by these products has been clarified ... I am most surprised that the USA manufacturers of the implicated blood products have not informed their customers of this new hazard. I assume no critical warning has been received in the United Kingdom?\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Preliminary Report Chapter 8: HIV and AIDS|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/preliminary-report/chapter-8/#footnote-10795-30-backlink|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk|language=en}}</ref> Despite Galbraith's warning the products were not withdrawn: a Department of Health letter considered that his suggestion was \"premature\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/preliminary-report/chapter-8/|title=Preliminary Report Chapter 8: HIV and AIDS|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1983 a leaflet distributed to UK blood donors answered the question as to whether AIDS could be transmitted by blood-products to be \"Almost certainly yes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/SGH0026675.PDF|title=Brochure : Aids and how it concerns blood donors|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1983 the UK Health Minister, Ken Clarke told parliament that \"There is no conclusive evidence that AIDS is transmitted by blood products\" and the importation of infected products continued. When giving evidence to the Penrose Inquiry, Dr Mark Winter said that at the time Ken Clarke made this statement \"all haemophilia clinicians by this stage clearly believed that commercial blood products could and were transmitting AIDS\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Report: Chapter 9 - Knowledge of the Geographical Spread and Prevalence of HIV/AIDS 1 |url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/text/354876_chapter_9.html#footnote-042-backlink |website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1984, Lord Glenarthur (Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the DHSS) said that \"It remains the case that there is no conclusive evidence of the transmission of AIDS through blood products, although the circumstantial evidence is strong\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/finalreport/pdf/SGH0076160.PDF|title=Letter to Government|website=Penroseinquiry.org.uk|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> and again the use of untreated Factor products and importation continued.\n\n== 2000 - Destroyed Evidence Investigation ==\nIn April 2000 the Department of Health published an internal audit to examine the loss of records relating to Hepatitis C litigation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Flint|first1=Caroline|title=Destroyed Documents (Blood Products)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060523/text/60523w0029.htm|website=Hansard|publisher=House of Commons}}</ref> The report concluded that \"an arbitrary and unjustified decision, most likely taken by an inexperienced member of staff, was responsible for the destruction of a series of files containing the minutes and background papers of the Advisory Committee on the Virological Safety of Blood (ACSVB)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58a18aeb2e69cf7248eeddbc/t/5b1a74a9352f53bcbf9a4c8c/1528460512936/DH+Audit+on+GEB.pdf|title=Internal Audit Review - Hepatitis C Litigation - Final Report|date=April 2000|website=Squarespace.com|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== 2009 \u2013 The Archer Report ==\nIn the early 2000s the former Solicitor General for England and Wales, [[Peter Archer, Baron Archer of Sandwell|Lord Archer]], campaigned for an inquiry into the tainted blood scandal alongside [[David Owen|Lord Owen]], who was the Health Minister from 1974 to 1976, [[Patrick Jenkin, Baron Jenkin of Roding|Lord Jenkin]], former Shadow Health Secretary, and others. They were unsuccessful.\n\nIn a 1990 episode of ''[[The Cook Report]]'', Owen said: \"I can see why some people would be unhappy with having all the facts revealed because it will show negligence\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cook Report \u2013 Profits Before Patients|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jb1Kb-WvW2o|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> In September 2016 Owen gave a speech in London during which he said the scandal had been covered-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uqt0xXz-saw|title=Lord David Owen \u2013 Bad Blood Speech 29/9/16|date=30 September 2016|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nArcher chaired a privately funded independent investigation set up in 2007. The Archer Report was published in 2009 and aimed to uncover the causes of the events that led to the thousands of infections and deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/delays-led-to-thousands-receiving-contaminated-blood-1629555.html|title=Delays Led to Thousands Receiving Contaminated Blood|author=Sam Marsden|website=Independent.co.uk|date=23 February 2009|accessdate=14 February 2010}}</ref> The report held no legal or official status and was unable to subpoena witnesses or demand the disclosure of documents.<ref name=PE1449/> Nonetheless, it sought to address the issue of missing evidence and documents relating to the scandal. For example, the ministerial papers of Lord Owen had been destroyed. \"We have been unable to ascertain who carried out the destruction of the papers, and who gave the instructions. But the conclusion appears inescapable that some official made a decision which he or she had no authority to make, or that someone was guilty of a serious error of judgement. The consequence is that Lord Owen has done his best to recollect details of events a quarter of a century ago, but both he, and we, have been deprived of the primary sources\", Archer reported. Lord Jenkin also voiced his difficulties obtaining documents for the inquiry, although the report stated: \"He subsequently received from the Department two bundles of documents. One of these was to be treated as confidential\". Lord Jenkin felt that the destruction of records was deliberate, and done \"in order to draw a line under the disaster\".<ref name=\"Archer Report\">{{Cite book |title=The Archer Inquiry |year=2009 |quote=On 13 April 2005 Lord Jenkin met Sir Nigel, who apologised for the original reply. Lord Jenkin was left with the clear impression from their subsequent conversation that all the files bearing upon the issue of contaminated blood products had been destroyed, and that this had been done 'with intent, in order to draw a line under the disaster'. |url=http://www.archercbbp.com/files/report/76_Lord%20Archer%20Report.DOC |access-date=1 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703132440/http://www.archercbbp.com/files/report/76_Lord%20Archer%20Report.DOC |archive-date=3 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAnother handling error is described in the inquiry: \"mishandling of documents arose in connection with a number of files relating to the Advisory Committee on the Virological Safety of Blood between May 1989 and February 1992 which were found to be missing\". The report went on to state: \"They were in fact destroyed over a period from July 1994 to March 1998\". When summarising these events it is stated \"some of those who gave evidence to us suspected that there was an exercise in suppressing evidence of negligence or misconduct.\"\n\n== 2015 \u2013 Scottish Penrose Inquiry ==\n{{Main|Penrose Inquiry}}\nIn 2008 the Scottish government announced [[Penrose Inquiry|a public inquiry]] into the scandal covering Scotland only, to be chaired by [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose|Lord Penrose]]. The inquiry's terms of reference outlined five deaths that were to be examined, but only one of those victims was a haemophiliac and that person had been infected with hepatitis C in the 1960s, before the factor concentrates were introduced.\n\nPublished in 2015, the inquiry was described as a [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] and waste of public money (over \u00a312 million) by critics after it made just one recommendation and failed to apportion any blame in the scandal. Its recommendation was to offer blood tests to anyone in Scotland who had a blood transfusion before 1991 and who had not already been tested for hepatitis C.\n\n== 2017 \u2013 Legal action and UK public inquiry ==\nIn July 2017 a group legal action ''Jason Evans & Ors'' was brought against the government on behalf of more than 500 people by Collins Solicitors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Momentum in Contaminated Blood Scandal grows as Collins apply for a Group Litigation Order \u2013 Collins Solicitors Press Release dated 4 July 2017|url=http://www.collinslaw.co.uk/post.php?s=2017-07-04-momentum-in-contaminated-blood-scandal-grows-as-collins-apply-for-a-group-litigation-order-collins-solicitors-press-release-dated-4-july-2017|website=Collinslaw.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ITV News \u2013 Families seek justice in Blood Scandal \u2013 4th July 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vCLXW4Mm5o|date=4 July 2017|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> After years of increasing pressure from campaigners and [[Member of parliament|MP]]s, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced a full UK-wide public inquiry into the scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Peter|last2=Topping|first2=Alexandra|title=Theresa May orders contaminated blood scandal inquiry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/11/contaminated-blood-scandal-theresa-may-orders-inquiry|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-40601013|title=Blood probe 'lessons must be learned'|work=BBC News|date=14 July 2017|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> In September 2017 a court ruling found in favour of the victims allowing them to launch a [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] action to seek damages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41406105|title=Victims win contaminated blood ruling|date=26 September 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/victims-and-families-can-bring-high-court-action-on-contaminated-blood-products/|title=Victims and families can bring High Court action on contaminated blood products|date=26 September 2017|work=Evening Express|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926200244/https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/news/uk/victims-and-families-can-bring-high-court-action-on-contaminated-blood-products/|archive-date=26 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-26/victims-and-families-win-high-court-ruling-to-seek-damages-over-contaminated-blood-products/|title=Victims and families win High Court ruling to seek damages over contaminated blood products|work=ITV News|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== 2018 \u2013 False ministerial statements withdrawn ==\nIn June 2018 the Department of Health issued an apology, because for two years Ministers had told Parliament that in relation to Contaminated Blood Scandal evidence: \"All documents up to 1995 are available through the National Archive\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Blood: Contamination:Written question \u2013 65851 |url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-27/65851/ |website=UK Parliament |language=English}}</ref>\n\n== 2019 \u2013 Files still missing ==\nIn February 2019, it emerged that around 450 files had been taken from the archives by staff from the Department of Health and Social Security, and not returned, sparking concerns among campaigners that the department was attempting a cover-up.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/contaminated-blood-scandal-documents-nhs-hiv-hepatitis-haemophilia-factor-8-cover-up-a8773716.html|title=Cover-up fears as hundreds of contaminated blood files 'vanish' before inquiry can see them|date=11 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Government support ==\nSuccessive governments, both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], have been criticised for their handling of the case, limited support schemes and refusal to conduct a public inquiry (until 2017). Some limited support has been provided to selected individuals through [[charitable trust]]s<ref name=\"auto\"/> which is often subject to [[means test]]ing, though no damages or compensation have ever been paid to UK victims or their families.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harpin|first1=Lee|title=Victims of contaminated blood scandal weren't given Tory compensation|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/victims-contaminated-blood-scandal-werent-10854692|website=mirror|date=22 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=In the urgent question on 16...: 21 Jan 2016: House of Commons debates - TheyWorkForYou|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2016-01-21b.1583.1|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 the Conservative government made \u00a342 million available to those affected by HIV,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2014-10-20/211081/|title=Blood: Contamination: Written question \u2013 211081|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=4 December 2017}}</ref> this equates to around \u00a329,000 on average between the 1,437 people who received a payment.\n\nIn 2017 the Conservatives announced more funds for those with first-stage chronic hepatitis C, but this additional money was reportedly to be sourced from funds for other tainted blood victims. The Department of Health was accused of robbing one set of victims to pay another. Officials stated that it had made available an extra \u00a3125 million, more than any previous government, but critics said this money was simply accounted for as a cost to the NHS of extending treatments to hepatitis C sufferers sooner.<ref name=PE1440>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=24 March 2017 |title=What a Hunt |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[HIV trial in Libya]] after over 400 children were infected with HIV at Libyan Children's Hospital.\n* [[Contaminated blood]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Contaminated haemophilia blood products|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProducts:End of 1st para: Adding additional reference to TNA (The National Archives).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contaminated_blood_scandal_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "List of most-wanted Nazi war criminals", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nSince 2002, [[Efraim Zuroff]] of the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] has produced an ''Annual Status Report on the Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]]'' which, since at least 2004, has included a list of \"most-wanted\" criminals who had never been convicted. The list was last updated in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zuroff |first1=Dr. Efraim |title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals: An Annual Status Report (April 1, 2017\u2013 March 31, 2018) |url=http://www.operationlastchance.org/PDF/ASR-2018.pdf |website=operationlastchance.org |publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center \u2013 Israel Office: Snider Social Action Institute  |format=PDF |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n== Nazi war criminals facing possible prosecution ==\nThe following Nazi war criminals were facing possible prosecution as of 2019, according to the Simon Wiesenthal Center. Current country of residence is listed first, with country where crime was committed enclosed in brackets. The 2018 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists seven men, of whom four are still alive:<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zuroff |first1=Dr. Efraim |title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals: An Annual Status Report (April 1, 2017\u2013 March 31, 2018) |url=http://www.operationlastchance.org/PDF/ASR-2018.pdf |website=operationlastchance.org |publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center \u2013 Israel Office: Snider Social Action Institute  |format=PDF |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (born 15 February 1924 (age {{age|1924|2|15}})) \u2013 Canada (Ukraine) \u2013 served in [[Einsatzkommando]] 10A (part of [[Einsatzkommando#Einsatzgruppe D|Einsatzgruppe D]]), which murdered an estimated 23,000 mostly Jewish civilians. In July 2016, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] refused to hear an appeal of a lower court decision that ordered the Canadian government to reconsider its decision to revoke Oberlander's Canadian citizenship. This means that to deport him so that he can be tried for war crimes, the government first has to prove that Oberlander was a willing participant in Nazi death squad activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/news/canada/jewish-groups-upset-supreme-courts-decision-oberlander|title=Jewish groups upset by Supreme Court's decision on Oberlander - The Canadian Jewish News|date=15 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2017 the Government of Canada used an [[Order in Council]] to strip Oberlander of his Canadian citizenship for the fourth time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/07/25/former-nazi-helmut-oberlander-stripped-of-citizenship-again.html|title=Former Nazi Helmut Oberlander stripped of citizenship again|first=Jeff|last=Outhit|date=25 July 2017|publisher=|via=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/helmut-oberlander-citizenship-stripped-fourth-time-1.4220666|title=Ex-Nazi interpreter Helmut Oberlander faces 'extraordinary' fourth fight over citizenship|publisher=}}</ref> This step was declared lawful by the Federal Court in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therecord.com/news-story/8930875-court-upholds-decision-to-revoke-helmut-oberlander-s-citizenship/|title=Court upholds decision to revoke Helmut Oberlander\u2019s citizenship|first=Jeff|last=Outhit|date=September 28, 2018|website=TheRecord.com}}</ref> The court's decision was upheld by the [[Federal Court of Appeal]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McQuigge |first1=Michelle |title=Court dismisses latest Oberlander effort to fight stripping of citizenship |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/oberlander-loses-latest-court-case-1.5111372 |accessdate=April 26, 2019 |work=CBC News |agency=Canadian press |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> On December 5, 2019, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] declined to hear Oberlander's appeal, clearing the way for his deportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/scoc-dismiss-appeal-2019-request-helmut-oberlander-1.5385186|title=Supreme Court won't hear appeal from former Nazi death squad interpreter|website=CBC|date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n# [[Kurt Gosdek]] (born {{birth based on age as of date|94|2017|9|28}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/germany-investigating-2-former-ss-death-squad-members/|title=Germany investigating 2 former SS death squad members|website=The Times of Israel|date=28 September 2017}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the [[Babi Yar]] massacre.\n# [[Herbert Wahler]] (born {{birth date and age|1921|12|10}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hna.de/lokales/melsungen/melsungen-ort45520/massaker-in-babi-jar-ex-ss-mann-96-soll-vor-gericht-9579864.html|title=Massacre with 33,771 dead in World War II: 96-year-old Melsunger is to go to court (Translation)|work=HNA|date=2 February 2018|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the Babi Yar massacre.\n# [[Wilhelm Karl Friedrich Hoffmeister]] (born {{birth based on age as of date|95|2018|6|6}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/world-news/2018/06/06/german-probe-targets-95-year-old-nazi-death-squad-suspect/|title=German probe targets 95-year-old Nazi death squad suspect|work=Shropshire Star|date=6 June 2018|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the Babi Yar massacre.\nThe 2016 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists eight people, of whom six are alive:\n# {{ill|Helma Kissner|pl|Helma Kissner}} (born {{birth date and age|1923|12|23}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/regionales/hamburg/article156213757/Geschichte-einer-Frau-die-unbedingt-zur-SS-wollte.html|title=Geschichte einer Frau, die unbedingt zur SS wollte|work=Welt|language=German|date=15 June 2016|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=sun>{{cite news |url=http://torontosun.com/2016/06/19/last-nazi-trial-mixed-success-with-prosecutions/wcm/ff82cdbb-5c28-4a8d-973f-e188d580875f |title=Last Nazi Trial: Mixed success with prosecutions |date=20 June 2016 |newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]] |last=Mandel |first=Michele |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Poland) \u2013 served as a radio operator in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]] from April to July 1944 \u2013 charged with accessory to murder in 260,000 cases.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Trial dates set in Germany in 2016.</ref> Ruled unfit to stand trial on 9 September 2016 by a court in Kiel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/09/auschwitz-radio-operator-ruled-unfit-stand-trial-germany-court-helma |title=Auschwitz radio operator ruled unfit to stand trial |author=Reuters |author-link=Reuters |date=9 September 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (mentioned above)\n# {{ill|Alfred Stork (soldier)|lt=Alfred Stork|it|Alfred Stork}} (born {{birth based on age as of date|92|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Germany (Greece) \u2013 Last-known news: former corporal convicted in absentia in 2013 by Rome Military Court for participating in the September 1943 [[Massacre of the Acqui Division|mass murder of 120 Italian officers on the Greek island of Cephalonia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Alfred Stork, Ex-Nazi War Criminal, Convicted In Absentia By Italian Court|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/18/alfred-stork-nazi-convicted_n_4124039.html|accessdate=January 21, 2016|work=World Post|agency=Associated Press|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Helmut Rasbol|pl}} (born Helmuth Leif Rasmussen; {{birth based on age as of date|90|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Denmark (Belarus) \u2013 (Last known location: Copenhagen, Denmark)<ref name=time/> during the years 1942\u20131943 served as a guard in the Judenlager established by the Nazis in [[Babruysk|Bobruisk]], Belarus, during which almost all the Jewish inmates of the camp were executed or died of the horrible physical conditions. In November 2016, the Danish chief prosecutor announced that Rasmussen would not face charges because of lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.dk/20161105/denmark-drops-probe-into-danish-nazi-camp-guard|title=Prosecutor drops probe into Danish Nazi camp guard|date=5 November 2016}}</ref> Now living under the surname Rasboel.<ref name=time/>\n# {{ill|Aksel Andersen (soldier)|lt=Aksel Andersen|pl|Aksel Andersen}} (born {{birth date and age|1924|6|18}}) \u2013 Denmark (Belarus) \u2013 Last known location: Sweden \u2013 during the years 1942\u20131943, he served as a guard in the Judenlager established by the Nazis in Bobruisk, Belarus, during which almost all the Jewish inmates of the camp were executed or died of the horrible physical conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=9505789&ct=14988127|title=Wiesenthal Center Rejects as Scandalous the Decision by Danish Prosecution to Permanently Close Investigation of Holocaust Crimes By Danish SS Volunteers in Belarus|work=Simon Wiesenthal Center|date=22 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bt.dk/danmark/91-aarig-dansker-blandt-de-mest-jagede-nazister-fra-anden-verdenskrig|title=91-\u00e5rig dansker blandt de mest jagede nazister fra Anden Verdenskrig|work=BT|language=Danish|date=11 May 2016}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Johann Robert Riss|pl}} (born {{birth based on age as of date|92|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Germany (Italy) \u2013 Last known news: on May 25, 2011, the former sergeant found guilty in absentia for the murder of 184 civilians in the [[Padule di Fucecchio massacre]] in Italy on August 23, 1944. He was sentenced to life in prison. Germany has declined to extradite Riss.<ref name=time>{{cite news|title=Here Are the 5 Most Wanted Nazi War Criminals|url=http://time.com/3958690/5-most-wanted-nazis/|accessdate=January 21, 2016|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=late>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32450169|title=Justice for historical crimes|first=William|last=Horsley|date=25 April 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists nine men, of which seven are alive:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=14583557|title=Wiesenthal Center 2015 Annual Report on the Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|date=13 April 2015|publisher=[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]|accessdate=18 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418063218/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=14583557|archive-date=18 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n# [[Gerhard Sommer]] (born {{birth date and age|1921|6|24}}; Last known location: Germany) Declared \"unfit for trial\" by a court in May 2015 due to severe dementia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alfred Stork, Ex-Nazi War Criminal, Convicted In Absentia By Italian Court|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/most-wanted-nazi-linked-to-italian-massacre-is-unfit-for-trial-says-german-court-10283430.html|accessdate=21 January 2016|work=The Independent|date=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Alfred Stork (soldier)|lt=Alfred Stork|it|Alfred Stork}} (mentioned earlier)\n# {{ill|Johann Robert Riss|pl}} (mentioned earlier)\n# X \u2013 {{ill|Helmut Rasbol|pl}} (mentioned earlier) \n# Y \u2013 unnamed person (Last known location: Germany) wanted for being accessory to the murder of [[Hungarian Jews]] in Auschwitz\n# Z \u2013 unnamed person (Last known location: Norway) wanted for murder of Jews in various locations in Poland and Ukraine\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (mentioned earlier)\n\n;Deceased\n;;2018 list:\n# [[Michael Karkoc]] (March 6, 1919 \u2013 December 14, 2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tributearchive.com/obituaries/9617462/Michael-Karkoc|title=Michael Karkoc|website=Tribute Archive}}</ref> \u2013 United States (Poland) \u2013 founding member and a lieutenant in the 2nd Company of the Ukrainian Self Defense Legion, which was one of the battalions of the [[Schutzmannschaft]] organized and sponsored by the Nazi German [[Schutzstaffel]], and which allegedly took part in war crimes against civilians in [[Ukraine]] and [[Poland]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">David Rising, Randy Herschaft and Monika Scislowska, Associated Press, ''[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/06/14/ap-impact-commander-in-ss-led-unit-living-in-us/2422427/ Commander in Nazi SS-led unit living in U.S.]'', June 14, 2013.</ref>  \n# [[Algimantas Dailide]] (12 March 1921 \u2013 2015) was an official of the Nazi-sponsored [[Lithuanian Security Police]] (Saugumas) during World War II.\n# {{ill|Jakiw \"Jakob\" Palij|pl|Jakob Palij}} (16 August 1923 in {{ill|P'yadyky|uk|\u041f'\u044f\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0438}}, [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] \u2013 9 January 2019 in [[Ahlen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ehemaliger-ss-scherge-jakiv-palij-gestorben-15982541.html|title=Ehemaliger SS-Scherge Jakiv Palij gestorben|website=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>) \u2013 Germany (Poland/Ukraine) \u2013 served as a guard in the [[Trawniki concentration camp]]. He was deported from [[Queens]] area of [[New York City]] in August 2018 to Germany, even though he had been stateless since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45257251|title=Nazi guard Palij deported by US to Germany|work=BBC|date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n;;2016 list:\n# [[Reinhold Hanning]] (28 December 1921 \u2013 30 May 2017) \u2013 Germany (Poland) \u2013 served in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]] from January 1943 until June 1944 \u2013 charged with accessory to murder in 170,000 cases.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Hanning was convicted and sentenced to 5 years' imprisonment on June 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36560416 |title=Former Auschwitz guard Reinhold Hanning convicted |date=17 June 2016 |newspaper=[[BBC]] |accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Never served his sentence as he died on 30 May 2017, aged 95, while awaiting appeal.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/world/reinhold-hanning-convicted-former-auschwitz-guard-dies-in-germany-at-95 |title=Reinhold Hanning, convicted former Auschwitz guard, dies in Germany at 95 |date=1 June 2017 |newspaper=[[National Post]] |author=The Associated Press |author-link=The Associated Press}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Jakiw \"Jakob\" Palij|pl|Jakob Palij}} (mentioned earlier)\n;;2015 list:\n# [[Vladimir Katriuk]] (1 October 1921 \u2013 22 May 2015; Last known location: Canada) Reported to have died in May 2015, aged 93.<ref name=obitglobe>{{cite news|title=Alleged Nazi war criminal sought by Russia dies in Quebe|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alleged-nazi-war-criminal-sought-by-russia-dies-in-quebec/article24667197/|accessdate=May 28, 2015|work=Globe and Mail|date=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n# [[Oskar Gr\u00f6ning]] (10 June 1921 \u2013 9 March 2018; Last known location: Germany). Trial in Hannover, Germany, July 2015. Found guilty of being accessory to murder of 300,000 people and sentenced to four years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/15/auschwitz-guard-oskar-groening-jailed-over-mass-murder|title=Former Auschwitz guard Oskar Gr\u00f6ning jailed over mass murder|first1=Kate|last1=Connolly|first2=|last2=Reuters|date=15 July 2015|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Named on previous lists==\n* [[Hans Lipschis|Hans (Antanus) Lipschis]] (Arrested in Germany, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22427976|title=Germany arrests 'former Auschwitz guard' Hans Lipschis|date=6 May 2013|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> found unfit for trial due to dementia. Died in Aalen in 2016, aged 96.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.die-apis.de/fileadmin/BEZIRKE/Aalen/Medien/Gemeinschaftsbl\u00e4ttle_Jan.-Apr._2017.pdf|title=Gemeinschaftsbl\u00e4ttle|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630214350/https://www.die-apis.de/fileadmin/BEZIRKE/Aalen/Medien/Gemeinschaftsbl%C3%A4ttle_Jan.-Apr._2017.pdf|archive-date=2018-06-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>)\n* [[Theodor Szehinskyj]] (age {{Age in years|1924}}. Last known location: United States), died in US 2014.\n* [[S\u00f8ren Kam]] \u2013 listed until 2014, died March 23, 2015\n* [[Ivan Kalymon|Ivan (John) Kalymon]] \u2013 listed until 2014, found in United States, lost US citizenship, died in 2014 while awaiting extradition to Germany<ref name=\"list2013\"/><ref>Matt Pearce, [http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-michigan-holocaust-20140709-story.html Holocaust suspect dies in Michigan after avoiding deportation], ''Los Angeles Times'' (July 9, 2014).</ref>\n*[[Aribert Heim]] \u2013 listed until 2013, death uncovered a year earlier<ref name=\"list2013\">{{cite book|title= Simon Wiesenthal Center 2013 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals|url= http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/NAZI-WAR-CRIMINALS-REPORT_2013.PDF|format= PDF|accessdate= 12 April 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140903150159/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/NAZI-WAR-CRIMINALS-REPORT_2013.PDF|archive-date= 3 September 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Alois Brunner]] \u2013 listed until 2013, presumed dead.<ref name=\"list2013\"/> In 2014, it was reported that he had died in Syria in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-in-syria-basement-in-2001-report/|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner died in Syria basement in 2001 \u2013 report|website=The Times of Israel|date=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Mikhail Gorshkow]] \u2013 fled to [[Estonia]] and stripped of his U.S. citizenship; listed until death in 2013.<ref name=\"list2013\"/> Cleared of charges in 2011 due to inconclusive evidence.<ref name=\"list2014\">{{cite book |format= [[PDF]] |publisher= Simon Wiesenthal Center |location= [[Los Angeles]] |year= 2014 |title= Simon Wiesenthal Center 2014 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals |url= http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF |accessdate= April 12, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181030024822/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPORT-V.2.PDF |archive-date= October 30, 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n* [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Csat\u00e1ry]] \u2013 listed until 2013,<ref name=\"list2013\"/> died 10 August 2013\n* [[Charles Zentai]] \u2013 listed until 2012,<ref name=\"list2012\">{{cite book|title=SWC Annual Status Report on the Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|year=2012|publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Centre|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/ANNUAL%20STATUS%20REPORT%20ON%20THE%20WORLDWIDE%20INVESTIGATION%20AND%20PROSECUTION%20OF%20NAZI%20WAR%20CRIMINALS.PDF |format= PDF|accessdate= 12 April 2015}}</ref> the Australian High Court ruled that Zentai could not be sent for trial to Hungary, alleging that the category of \"War Crimes\" did not exist at that time in Hungarian law, died 13 December 2017\n*[[Klaas Carel Faber]] \u2013 listed until 2012,<ref name=\"list2012\"/> died in the process of extradition from Germany to Netherlands on 24 May 2012, aged 90.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dashboard.i-pers.nl/home/Show/9151d8935b94c9e2f1beea3f5be534af |title=Klaas Faber: de laatste Nedernazi is dood |work=De Nieuwe Pers |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120529001017/http://dashboard.i-pers.nl/home/Show/9151d8935b94c9e2f1beea3f5be534af |archivedate=29 May 2012 }}</ref>\n*[[S\u00e1ndor K\u00e9p\u00edr\u00f3]] \u2013 listed until 2011,<ref name=\"list2011\">{{cite news|title=Simon Wiesenthal Center's Tenth Annual Report on the Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=6478433&ct=9378529|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=Simon Wiesenthal Centre|date=1 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814174628/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=6478433&ct=9378529|archive-date=14 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> tried and found not guilty that year; died 3 September 2011.\n*[[Adam Nagorny]] \u2013 listed until 2011,<ref name=\"list2011\"/> died 2011.<ref>http://www.operationlastchance.org/PDF/26.1-12.doc</ref>\n*[[Milivoj A\u0161ner]] \u2013 listed until 2011,<ref name=\"list2011\"/> died 14 June 2011.\n*[[Samuel Kunz]] \u2013 listed until 2010,<ref name=\"list2010\"/> died 18 November 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/22/nazi-suspect-samuel-kunz-dies-trial|title=Suspected Nazi death camp guard Samuel Kunz dies before trial|date=22 November 2010 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|first=Alexandra|last=Topping|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n*[[Adolf Storms]] \u2013 listed until 2010,<ref name=\"list2010\">{{cite news|last=Zuroff|first=Ephraim|title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/ASR-2010.PDF|format=PDF|accessdate=6 May  2012|newspaper=Simon Wiesenthal Center|date=31 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160103075644/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/ASR-2010.PDF|archive-date=3 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> died 28 June 2010 while awaiting trial.\n*[[Peter Egner]] \u2013 listed until 2010,<ref name=\"list2010\"/> died January 2011 while awaiting trial.<ref>{{cite news|last=Myers|first=Laura|title=Accused Nazi dies just before US citizenship trial|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/01/31/us-nazi-death-idUKTRE70U6D720110131|accessdate=6 May 2012|date=31 January 2011}}</ref>\n*[[John Demjanjuk|Ivan Demjanjuk]] \u2013 listed until 2009,<ref name=\"list2009\">{{cite news|title=Wiesenthal Center Annual Report on the Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=6929435|accessdate=May 6, 2012|newspaper=Simon Wiesenthal Centre|date=April 20, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213122700/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=6929435|archive-date=December 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> deported to Germany for trial in 2009, and was convicted in 2011 pending appeal, died 17 March 2012. He died before his appeal could be tried by the German Appellate Court, and as a result, his previous conviction was not upheld. A few days after his death, the German court clarified that, according to German law, Demjanjuk was \"presumed innocent\", that he did not have a criminal record, and that his previous interim conviction was invalidated.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aderet|first=Ofer|title=Convicted Nazi criminal Demjanjuk deemed innocent in Germany over technicality |date=23 March 2012|accessdate=1 July  2012|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/convicted-nazi-criminal-demjanjuk-deemed-innocent-in-germany-over-technicality-1.420280|work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref>\n*[[Heinrich Boere]] \u2013 listed until 2009,<ref name=\"list2009\"/> convicted 2010 and sentenced to life in prison. Died December 1, 2013.\n*[[Harry M\u00e4nnil]] \u2013 listed until 2009,<ref name=\"list2009\"/> cleared of charges in 2005 after four-year investigation,<ref name=\"postimees\">{{cite news|url=http://www.euro.postimees.ee/311205/online_uudised/187471.php|title=Kaitsepolitsei ei leidnud Harry M\u00e4nnilil veres\u00fc\u00fcd|date=20 December 2005|newspaper=Postimees|language=Estonian|accessdate=16 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130106130342/http://www.euro.postimees.ee/311205/online_uudised/187471.php|archivedate=6 January 2013}}</ref> died 11 January 2010.\n*[[Erna Wallisch]] \u2013 listed until 2007,<ref name=\"list2007\">{{cite web|title=Wiesenthal Center Annual Report Notes Rise in Number of Convictions of Nazi War Criminals During Past Year; Slams Austria, Germany and Twelve Others for Failure to Bring Holocaust Perpetrators to Justice; Praises US and Italy for Continued Successes|work=Simon Wiesenthal Center News Release|publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center|date=15 April 2007|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442245&ct=5851509|accessdate=7 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605055334/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442245&ct=5851509|archive-date=5 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> died 21 February 2008 while under investigation.\n*[[Lajos Polg\u00e1r]] \u2013 listed until 2006,<ref name=\"list2006\">{{cite news|title=Wiesenthal Center Annual Report on Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442247&ct=5850977|accessdate=26 April 2013|date=23 April 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419030011/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442247&ct=5850977|archive-date=19 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> died 12 July 2006.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnston|first=Chris|title=War crimes suspect dies amid controversy|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/war-crimes-suspect-dies-amid-controversy/2006/07/13/1152637752956.html|accessdate=May 6, 2012|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=13 July 2006}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Ladislav Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|de}} \u2013 listed until 2005,<ref name=\"list2005\">{{cite news|title=SWC Annual Report on Nazi War Criminals Reveals Dramatic Rise in New Investigations; Slams Ukraine and Others; & Praises US for Outstanding Success|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442249&ct=5851679|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=Simon Wiesenthal Center|date=4 May 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014650/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4442249&ct=5851679|archive-date=19 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> tried in 2005 and acquitted by German court due to lack of reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Nazi officer acquitted of three massacres|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10533485|accessdate=6 May 2005|newspaper=Associated Press|date=19 December 2005}}</ref> Died 23 December 2011.<ref>[http://tvnoviny.sk/sekcia/spravy/zahranicne/zomrel-byvaly-velitel-edelweiss-niznansky.html Ladislav Niznansky profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317221116/http://tvnoviny.sk/sekcia/spravy/zahranicne/zomrel-byvaly-velitel-edelweiss-niznansky.html |date=2012-03-17 }}, tvnoviny.sk; accessed 13 November 2014.</ref>\n*[[Jakob Reimer|Jack Reimer]] \u2013 listed until 2005,<ref name=\"list2005\"/> extradition granted but died before he could be deported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themennonite.org/issues/15-3/articles/Mennonites_and_the_Holocaust |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529024556/http://www.themennonite.org/issues/15-3/articles/Mennonites_and_the_Holocaust |archivedate=2014-05-29 }}</ref>\n*[[Dinko \u0160aki\u0107|Nada \u0160aki\u0107]] \u2013 listed until 2004. Died 2008.<ref name=\"list2004\">{{cite news|title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals (1 April 2003 \u2013 31 March 2004). An Annual Status Report|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B4BBE989B-D21C-4116-BC6F-92CE75144F83%7D/WWInvestigation.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=26 April 2013|date=August 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204224/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B4BBE989B-D21C-4116-BC6F-92CE75144F83%7D/WWInvestigation.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Rosemarie Albrecht|de}} \u2013 listed until 2004,<ref name=\"list2004\"/> died 7 January 2008.\n*[[Petras Bernatavicius]] \u2013 listed until 2004,<ref name=\"list2004\"/> found to have died in 1992.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Post-war flight of Nazi fugitives |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Most-wanted Nazi war criminals}}\n[[Category:Nazi war criminals]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted on war crimes charges|Nazi]]\n[[Category:Most Wanted lists|Nazi]]\n[[Category:Simon Wiesenthal Center]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Nazi-related lists]]\n[[Category:21st century-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nSince 2002, [[Efraim Zuroff]] of the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] has produced an ''Annual Status Report on the Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]]'' which, since at least 2004, has included a list of \"most-wanted\" criminals who had never been convicted. The list was last updated in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zuroff |first1=Dr. Efraim |title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals: An Annual Status Report (April 1, 2017\u2013 March 31, 2018) |url=http://www.operationlastchance.org/PDF/ASR-2018.pdf |website=operationlastchance.org |publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center \u2013 Israel Office: Snider Social Action Institute  |format=PDF |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n== Nazi war criminals facing possible prosecution ==\nThe following Nazi war criminals were facing possible prosecution as of 2019, according to the Simon Wiesenthal Center. Current country of residence is listed first, with country where crime was committed enclosed in brackets. The 2018 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists seven men, of whom four are still alive:<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zuroff |first1=Dr. Efraim |title=Worldwide Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals: An Annual Status Report (April 1, 2017\u2013 March 31, 2018) |url=http://www.operationlastchance.org/PDF/ASR-2018.pdf |website=operationlastchance.org |publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center \u2013 Israel Office: Snider Social Action Institute  |format=PDF |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (born 15 February 1924 (age {{age|1924|2|15}})) \u2013 Canada (Ukraine) \u2013 served in [[Einsatzkommando]] 10A (part of [[Einsatzkommando#Einsatzgruppe D|Einsatzgruppe D]]), which murdered an estimated 23,000 mostly Jewish civilians. In July 2016, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] refused to hear an appeal of a lower court decision that ordered the Canadian government to reconsider its decision to revoke Oberlander's Canadian citizenship. This means that to deport him so that he can be tried for war crimes, the government first has to prove that Oberlander was a willing participant in Nazi death squad activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/news/canada/jewish-groups-upset-supreme-courts-decision-oberlander|title=Jewish groups upset by Supreme Court's decision on Oberlander - The Canadian Jewish News|date=15 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2017 the Government of Canada used an [[Order in Council]] to strip Oberlander of his Canadian citizenship for the fourth time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/07/25/former-nazi-helmut-oberlander-stripped-of-citizenship-again.html|title=Former Nazi Helmut Oberlander stripped of citizenship again|first=Jeff|last=Outhit|date=25 July 2017|publisher=|via=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/helmut-oberlander-citizenship-stripped-fourth-time-1.4220666|title=Ex-Nazi interpreter Helmut Oberlander faces 'extraordinary' fourth fight over citizenship|publisher=}}</ref> This step was declared lawful by the Federal Court in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therecord.com/news-story/8930875-court-upholds-decision-to-revoke-helmut-oberlander-s-citizenship/|title=Court upholds decision to revoke Helmut Oberlander\u2019s citizenship|first=Jeff|last=Outhit|date=September 28, 2018|website=TheRecord.com}}</ref> The court's decision was upheld by the [[Federal Court of Appeal]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McQuigge |first1=Michelle |title=Court dismisses latest Oberlander effort to fight stripping of citizenship |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/oberlander-loses-latest-court-case-1.5111372 |accessdate=April 26, 2019 |work=CBC News |agency=Canadian press |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> On December 5, 2019, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] declined to hear Oberlander's appeal, clearing the way for his deportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/scoc-dismiss-appeal-2019-request-helmut-oberlander-1.5385186|title=Supreme Court won't hear appeal from former Nazi death squad interpreter|website=CBC|date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n# [[Kurt Gosdek]] (born {{birth based on age as of date|94|2017|9|28}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/germany-investigating-2-former-ss-death-squad-members/|title=Germany investigating 2 former SS death squad members|website=The Times of Israel|date=28 September 2017}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the [[Babi Yar]] massacre.\n# [[Herbert Wahler]] (born {{birth date and age|1921|12|10}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hna.de/lokales/melsungen/melsungen-ort45520/massaker-in-babi-jar-ex-ss-mann-96-soll-vor-gericht-9579864.html|title=Massacre with 33,771 dead in World War II: 96-year-old Melsunger is to go to court (Translation)|work=HNA|date=2 February 2018|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the Babi Yar massacre.\n# [[Wilhelm Karl Friedrich Hoffmeister]] (born {{birth based on age as of date|95|2018|6|6}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/world-news/2018/06/06/german-probe-targets-95-year-old-nazi-death-squad-suspect/|title=German probe targets 95-year-old Nazi death squad suspect|work=Shropshire Star|date=6 June 2018|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Ukraine) \u2013 accused of being involved in the Babi Yar massacre.\nThe 2016 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists eight people, of whom six are alive:\n# {{ill|Helma Kissner|pl|Helma Kissner}} (born {{birth date and age|1923|12|23}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/regionales/hamburg/article156213757/Geschichte-einer-Frau-die-unbedingt-zur-SS-wollte.html|title=Geschichte einer Frau, die unbedingt zur SS wollte|work=Welt|language=German|date=15 June 2016|access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=sun>{{cite news |url=http://torontosun.com/2016/06/19/last-nazi-trial-mixed-success-with-prosecutions/wcm/ff82cdbb-5c28-4a8d-973f-e188d580875f |title=Last Nazi Trial: Mixed success with prosecutions |date=20 June 2016 |newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]] |last=Mandel |first=Michele |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref> \u2013 Germany (Poland) \u2013 served as a radio operator in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]] from April to July 1944 \u2013 charged with accessory to murder in 260,000 cases.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Trial dates set in Germany in 2016.</ref> Ruled unfit to stand trial on 9 September 2016 by a court in Kiel.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/09/auschwitz-radio-operator-ruled-unfit-stand-trial-germany-court-helma |title=Auschwitz radio operator ruled unfit to stand trial |author=Reuters |author-link=Reuters |date=9 September 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (mentioned above)\n# {{ill|Alfred Stork (soldier)|lt=Alfred Stork|it|Alfred Stork}} (born {{birth based on age as of date|92|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Germany (Greece) \u2013 Last-known news: former corporal convicted in absentia in 2013 by Rome Military Court for participating in the September 1943 [[Massacre of the Acqui Division|mass murder of 120 Italian officers on the Greek island of Cephalonia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Alfred Stork, Ex-Nazi War Criminal, Convicted In Absentia By Italian Court|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/18/alfred-stork-nazi-convicted_n_4124039.html|accessdate=January 21, 2016|work=World Post|agency=Associated Press|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Helmut Rasbol|pl}} (born Helmuth Leif Rasmussen; {{birth based on age as of date|90|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Denmark (Belarus) \u2013 (Last known location: Copenhagen, Denmark)<ref name=time/> during the years 1942\u20131943 served as a guard in the Judenlager established by the Nazis in [[Babruysk|Bobruisk]], Belarus, during which almost all the Jewish inmates of the camp were executed or died of the horrible physical conditions. In November 2016, the Danish chief prosecutor announced that Rasmussen would not face charges because of lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.dk/20161105/denmark-drops-probe-into-danish-nazi-camp-guard|title=Prosecutor drops probe into Danish Nazi camp guard|date=5 November 2016}}</ref> Now living under the surname Rasboel.<ref name=time/>\n# {{ill|Aksel Andersen (soldier)|lt=Aksel Andersen|pl|Aksel Andersen}} (born {{birth date and age|1924|6|18}}) \u2013 Denmark (Belarus) \u2013 Last known location: Sweden \u2013 during the years 1942\u20131943, he served as a guard in the Judenlager established by the Nazis in Bobruisk, Belarus, during which almost all the Jewish inmates of the camp were executed or died of the horrible physical conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=9505789&ct=14988127|title=Wiesenthal Center Rejects as Scandalous the Decision by Danish Prosecution to Permanently Close Investigation of Holocaust Crimes By Danish SS Volunteers in Belarus|work=Simon Wiesenthal Center|date=22 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bt.dk/danmark/91-aarig-dansker-blandt-de-mest-jagede-nazister-fra-anden-verdenskrig|title=91-\u00e5rig dansker blandt de mest jagede nazister fra Anden Verdenskrig|work=BT|language=Danish|date=11 May 2016}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Johann Robert Riss|pl}} (born {{birth based on age as of date|92|2015|7|15}})<ref name=time/> \u2013 Germany (Italy) \u2013 Last known news: on May 25, 2011, the former sergeant found guilty in absentia for the murder of 184 civilians in the [[Padule di Fucecchio massacre]] in Italy on August 23, 1944. He was sentenced to life in prison. Germany has declined to extradite Riss.<ref name=time>{{cite news|title=Here Are the 5 Most Wanted Nazi War Criminals|url=http://time.com/3958690/5-most-wanted-nazis/|accessdate=January 21, 2016|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=late>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32450169|title=Justice for historical crimes|first=William|last=Horsley|date=25 April 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 2015 ''Annual [[List of Axis personnel indicted for war crimes|Nazi war criminals]] report'' lists nine men, of which seven are alive:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=14583557|title=Wiesenthal Center 2015 Annual Report on the Investigation and Prosecution of Nazi War Criminals|date=13 April 2015|publisher=[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]|accessdate=18 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418063218/http://www.wiesenthal.com/site/apps/nlnet/content2.aspx?c=lsKWLbPJLnF&b=4441467&ct=14583557|archive-date=18 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n# [[Gerhard Sommer]] (born {{birth date and age|1921|6|24}}; Last known location: Germany) Declared \"unfit for trial\" by a court in May 2015 due to severe dementia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alfred Stork, Ex-Nazi War Criminal, Convicted In Absentia By Italian Court|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/most-wanted-nazi-linked-to-italian-massacre-is-unfit-for-trial-says-german-court-10283430.html|accessdate=21 January 2016|work=The Independent|date=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Alfred Stork (soldier)|lt=Alfred Stork|it|Alfred Stork}} (mentioned earlier)\n# {{ill|Johann Robert Riss|pl}} (mentioned earlier)\n# X \u2013 {{ill|Helmut Rasbol|pl}} (mentioned earlier) \n# Y \u2013 unnamed person (Last known location: Germany) wanted for being accessory to the murder of [[Hungarian Jews]] in Auschwitz\n# Z \u2013 unnamed person (Last known location: Norway) wanted for murder of Jews in various locations in Poland and Ukraine\n# [[Helmut Oberlander]] (mentioned earlier)\n\n;Deceased\n;;2018 list:\n# [[Michael Karkoc]] (March 6, 1919 \u2013 December 14, 2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tributearchive.com/obituaries/9617462/Michael-Karkoc|title=Michael Karkoc|website=Tribute Archive}}</ref> \u2013 United States (Poland) \u2013 founding member and a lieutenant in the 2nd Company of the Ukrainian Self Defense Legion, which was one of the battalions of the [[Schutzmannschaft]] organized and sponsored by the Nazi German [[Schutzstaffel]], and which allegedly took part in war crimes against civilians in [[Ukraine]] and [[Poland]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">David Rising, Randy Herschaft and Monika Scislowska, Associated Press, ''[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/06/14/ap-impact-commander-in-ss-led-unit-living-in-us/2422427/ Commander in Nazi SS-led unit living in U.S.]'', June 14, 2013.</ref>  \n# [[Algimantas Dailide]] (12 March 1921 \u2013 2015) was an official of the Nazi-sponsored [[Lithuanian Security Police]] (Saugumas) during World War II.\n# {{ill|Jakiw \"Jakob\" Palij|pl|Jakob Palij}} (16 August 1923 in {{ill|P'yadyky|uk|\u041f'\u044f\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0438}}, [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] \u2013 9 January 2019 in [[Ahlen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ehemaliger-ss-scherge-jakiv-palij-gestorben-15982541.html|title=Ehemaliger SS-Scherge Jakiv Palij gestorben|website=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|language=German|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>) \u2013 Germany (Poland/Ukraine) \u2013 served as a guard in the [[Trawniki concentration camp]]. He was deported from [[Queens]] area of [[New York City]] in August 2018 to Germany, even though he had been stateless since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45257251|title=Nazi guard Palij deported by US to Germany|work=BBC|date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n;;2016 list:\n# [[Reinhold Hanning]] (28 December 1921 \u2013 30 May 2017) \u2013 Germany (Poland) \u2013 served in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]] from January 1943 until June 1944 \u2013 charged with accessory to murder in 170,000 cases.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Hanning was convicted and sentenced to 5 years' imprisonment on June 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36560416 |title=Former Auschwitz guard Reinhold Hanning convicted |date=17 June 2016 |newspaper=[[BBC]] |accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> Never served his sentence as he died on 30 May 2017, aged 95, while awaiting appeal.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/world/reinhold-hanning-convicted-former-auschwitz-guard-dies-in-germany-at-95 |title=Reinhold Hanning, convicted former Auschwitz guard, dies in Germany at 95 |date=1 June 2017 |newspaper=[[National Post]] |author=The Associated Press |author-link=The Associated Press}}</ref>\n# {{ill|Jakiw \"Jakob\" Palij|pl|Jakob Palij}} (mentioned earlier)\n;;2015 list:\n# [[Vladimir Katriuk]] (1 October 1921 \u2013 22 May 2015; Last known location: Canada) Reported to have died in May 2015, aged 93.<ref name=obitglobe>{{cite news|title=Alleged Nazi war criminal sought by Russia dies in Quebe|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/alleged-nazi-war-criminal-sought-by-russia-dies-in-quebec/article24667197/|accessdate=May 28, 2015|work=Globe and Mail|date=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n# [[Oskar Gr\u00f6ning]] (10 June 1921 \u2013 9 March 2018; Last known location: Germany). Trial in Hannover, Germany, July 2015. Found guilty of being accessory to murder of 300,000 people and sentenced to four years' imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/15/auschwitz-guard-oskar-groening-jailed-over-mass-murder|title=Former Auschwitz guard Oskar Gr\u00f6ning jailed over mass murder|first1=Kate|last1=Connolly|first2=|last2=Reuters|date=15 July 2015|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Named on previous lists==\n* [[Hans Lipschis|Hans (Antanus) Lipschis]] (Arrested in Germany, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22427976|title=Germany arrests 'former Auschwitz guard' Hans Lipschis|date=6 May 2013|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> found unfit for trial due to dementia. Died in Aalen in 2016, aged 96.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.die-apis.de/fileadmin/BEZIRKE/Aalen/Medien/Gemeinschaftsbl\u00e4ttle_Jan.-Apr._2017.pdf|title=Gemeinschaftsbl\u00e4ttle|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630214350/https://www.die-apis.de/fileadmin/BEZIRKE/Aalen/Medien/Gemeinschaftsbl%C3%A4ttle_Jan.-Apr._2017.pdf|archive-date=2018-06-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>)\n* [[Theodor Szehinskyj]] (age {{Age in years|1924}}. Last known location: United States), died in US 2014.\n* [[S\u00f8ren Kam]] \u2013 listed until 2014, died March 23, 2015\n* [[Ivan Kalymon|Ivan (John) Kalymon]] \u2013 listed until 2014, found in United States, lost US citizenship, died in 2014 while awaiting extradition to Germany<ref name=\"list2013\"/><ref>Matt Pearce, [http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-michigan-holocaust-20140709-story.html Holocaust suspect dies in Michigan after avoiding deportation], ''Los Angeles Times'' (July 9, 2014).</ref>\n*[[Aribert Heim]] \u2013 listed until 2013, death uncovered a year earlier<ref name=\"list2013\">{{cite book|title= Simon Wiesenthal Center 2013 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals|url= http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/NAZI-WAR-CRIMINALS-REPORT_2013.PDF|format= PDF|accessdate= 12 April 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140903150159/http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/NAZI-WAR-CRIMINALS-REPORT_2013.PDF|archive-date= 3 September 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Alois Brunner]] \u2013 listed until 2013, presumed dead.<ref name=\"list2013\"/> In 2014, it was reported that he had died in Syria in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/nazi-war-criminal-alois-brunner-died-in-syria-basement-in-2001-report/|title=Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner died in Syria basement in 2001 \u2013 report|website=The Times of Isreal|date=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Mikhail Gorshkow]] \u2013 fled to [[Estonia]] and stripped of his U.S. citizenship; listed until death in 2013.<ref name=\"list2013\"/> Cleared of charges in 2011 due to inconclusive evidence.<ref name=\"list2014\">{{cite book |format= [[PDF]] |publisher= Simon Wiesenthal Center |location= [[Los Angeles]] |year= 2014 |title= Simon Wiesenthal Center 2014 Annual Report on the Status of Nazi War Criminals |url= http://www.wiesenthal.com/atf/cf/%7B54d385e6-f1b9-4e9f-8e94-890c3e6dd277%7D/WIESENTHAL-CENTER_2014-ANNUAL-NAZI-WAR-CRIMNAL-REPOR