{"title_page": "Ursescu theorem", "text_new": "In mathematics, particularly in [[functional analysis]] and [[convex analysis]], the Ursescu theorem is a theorem that generalizes the [[Closed graph theorem]], the [[Open mapping theorem (functional analysis)|Open Mapping theorem]], and the [[Uniform boundedness principle]].\n\n==Ursescu Theorem==\n\nThe following notation and notions are used, where <math>\\mathcal{R} : X \\rightrightarrows Y</math> is a [[multifunction]] and ''S'' is a non-empty subset of a [[topological vector space]] ''X'':\n* the [[affine span]] of ''S'' is denoted by <math>\\operatorname{aff} S</math> and the [[linear span]] is denoted by <math>\\operatorname{span} S</math>.\n* <math>{}^{i}S</math> denotes the [[algebraic interior]] of ''S'' (in ''X'').\n* <math>{}^{ib}S := {}^{i}S</math> if <math>\\operatorname{span} \\left( S - s_0 \\right)</math> is [[Barrelled space|barreled]] for some/every <math>s_0 \\in S</math> while <math>{}^{ib}S := \\emptyset</math> otherwise.\n** It can be shown that for any ''x'' in ''X'', <math>x \\in {}^{ib} S</math> if and only if the cone generated by <math>S - x</math> (i.e. <math>\\cup_{n \\in \\mathbb{N}} n \\left( S - x \\right)</math>) is a barreled linear subspace of ''X''\n* The '''domain of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{Dom} \\mathcal{R} := \\left\\{ x \\in X : \\mathcal{R}(x) \\neq \\emptyset \\right\\}</math>.\n* The '''image of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} := \\cup_{x \\in X} \\mathcal{R}(x)</math>.\n* The '''graph of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{gr} \\mathcal{R} := \\left\\{ (x, y) \\in X \\times Y : y \\in \\mathcal{R}(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n* <math>\\mathcal{R}</math> is '''closed''' (respectively, '''convex''') if the graph of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math> is closed (resp. convex) in <math>X \\times Y</math>.\n* The '''inverse of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is the multifunction <math>\\mathcal{R}^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math> defined by <math>\\mathcal{R}^{-1}(y) := \\left\\{ x \\in X : y \\in \\mathcal{R}(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n** Note that if <math>f : X \\to Y</math> is a function, then its inverse is the multifunction <math>f^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math> obtained from canonically identifying ''f'' with the multifunction ''f : X <math>\\rightrightarrows</math> Y'' defined by <math>x \\mapsto \\left\\{ f(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n* <math>\\operatorname{int}_T S</math> is the [[interior (topology)|interior]] of ''S'' with respect to ''T'', where <math>S \\subseteq T</math>.\n* <math>\\operatorname{rint} S := \\operatorname{int}_{\\operatorname{aff} S} S</math> is the [[interior (topology)|interior]] of ''S'' with respect to <math>\\operatorname{aff} S</math>.\n\n===Statement===\n('''Ursescu'''){{sfn | Zalinescu | 2002 | p=23}} Let ''X'' be a [[complete]] [[semi-metrizable]] [[locally convex]] [[topological vector space]] and <math>\\mathcal{R} : X \\rightrightarrows Y</math> be a [[closed]] [[convex]] multifunction with non-empty domain. \nAssume that <math>\\operatorname{span} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} - y \\right)</math> is [[Barrelled space|barreled]] for some/every <math>y \\in \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R}</math>. Assume that <math>y_0 \\in {}^{i}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math> and let <math>x_0 \\in \\mathcal{R}^{-1}\\left( y_0 \\right)</math> (so that <math>y_0 \\in \\mathcal{R}\\left( x_0 \\right)</math>). Then for every neighborhood ''U'' of <math>x_0</math> in ''X'', <math>y_0</math> belongs to the relative interior of <math>\\mathcal{R}\\left( U \\right)</math> in <math>\\operatorname{aff} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math> (i.e. <math>y_0 \\in \\operatorname{int}_{\\operatorname{aff} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)} \\mathcal{R}\\left( U \\right)</math>). \nIn particular, if <math>{}^{ib}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) \\neq \\emptyset</math> then <math>{}^{ib}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) = {}^{i}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) = \\operatorname{rint} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math>.\n\n==Corollaries==\n\n===Closed graph theorem===\n\n('''[[Closed graph theorem]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and ''T : X \\to Y'' be a linear map. Then ''T'' is continuous if and only if the graph of ''T'' is closed in <math>X \\times Y</math>.\n\n'''Proof: '''\nFor the non-trivial direction, assume that the graph of ''T'' is closed and let <math>\\mathcal{R} := T^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math>. It is easy to see that <math>\\operatorname{gr} \\mathcal{R}</math> is closed and convex and that its image is ''X''. \nGiven ''x'' in ''X'', ''(T x, x)'' belongs to <math>Y \\times X</math> so that for every open neighborhood ''V'' of ''T x'' in ''Y'', <math>\\mathcal{R}(V) = T^{-1}(V)</math> is a neighborhood of ''x'' in ''X''. \nThus ''T'' is continuous at ''x''. \nQ.E.D.\n\n===Uniform boundedness principle===\n\n('''[[Uniform boundedness principle]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and <math>T : X \\to Y</math> be a bijective linear map. Then ''T'' is continuous if and only if <math>T^{-1} : Y \\to X</math> is continuous. Furthermore, if ''T'' is continuous then ''T'' is an isomorphism of [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s.\n\n'''Proof: '''\nApply the closed graph theorem to ''T'' and <math>T^{-1}</math>. \nQ.E.D.\n\n===Open mapping theorem===\n\n('''[[Open mapping theorem]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and <math>T : X \\to Y</math> be a continuous linear map. Then T is an [[open map]].\n\n'''Proof: '''\nClearly, ''T'' is a closed and convex relation whose image is ''Y''. \nLet ''U'' be a non-empty open subset of ''X'', let ''y'' be in ''T(U)'', and let ''x'' in ''U'' be such that ''y = T x''. \nFrom the Ursescu theorem it follows that ''T(U)'' is a neighborhood of ''y''. \nQ.E.D.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Closed graph theorem]]\n* [[convex]]\n* [[Open mapping theorem]]\n* [[Uniform boundedness principle]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book | last=Zalinescu | first=C | title=Convex analysis in general vector spaces | publisher=World Scientific | publication-place=River Edge, N.J. London | year=2002 | isbn=981-238-067-1 | oclc=285163112 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Baggs|first=Ivan|date=1974|title=Functions with a closed graph|url=https://www.ams.org/|journal=Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society|language=en|volume=43|issue=2|pages=439\u2013442|doi=10.1090/S0002-9939-1974-0334132-8|issn=0002-9939}}\n\n{{Functional Analysis}}\n\n[[Category:Theorems in functional analysis]]\n", "text_old": "In mathematics, particularly in [[functional analysis]] and [[convex analysis]], the Ursescu theorem is a theorem that generalizes the [[Closed graph theorem]], the [[Open mapping theorem (functional analysis)|Open Mapping theorem]], and the [[Uniform boundedness principle]].\n\n==Ursescu Theorem==\n\nThe following notation and notions are used, where <math>\\mathcal{R} : X \\rightrightarrows Y</math> is a [[multifunction]] and ''S'' is a non-empty subset of a [[topological vector space]] ''X'':\n* the [[affine span]] of ''S'' is denoted by <math>\\operatorname{aff} S</math> and the [[linear span]] is denoted by <math>\\operatorname{span} S</math>.\n* <math>{}^{i}S</math> denotes the [[algebraic interior]] of ''S'' (in ''X'').\n* <math>{}^{ib}S := {}^{i}S</math> if <math>\\operatorname{span} \\left( S - s_0 \\right)</math> is [[Barrelled space|barreled]] for some/every <math>s_0 \\in S</math> while <math>{}^{ib}S := \\emptyset</math> otherwise.\n** It can be shown that for any ''x'' in ''X'', <math>x \\in {}^{ib} S</math> if and only if the cone generated by <math>S - x</math> (i.e. <math>\\cup_{n \\in \\mathbb{N}} n \\left( S - x \\right)</math>) is a barreled linear subspace of ''X''\n* The '''domain of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{Dom} \\mathcal{R} := \\left\\{ x \\in X : \\mathcal{R}(x) \\neq \\emptyset \\right\\}</math>.\n* The '''image of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} := \\cup_{x \\in X} \\mathcal{R}(x)</math>.\n* The '''graph of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is <math>\\operatorname{gr} \\mathcal{R} := \\left\\{ (x, y) \\in X \\times Y : y \\in \\mathcal{R}(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n* <math>\\mathcal{R}</math> is '''closed''' (respectively, '''convex''') if the graph of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math> is closed (resp. convex) in <math>X \\times Y</math>.\n* The '''inverse of <math>\\mathcal{R}</math>''' is the multifunction <math>\\mathcal{R}^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math> defined by <math>\\mathcal{R}^{-1}(y) := \\left\\{ x \\in X : y \\in \\mathcal{R}(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n** Note that if <math>f : X \\to Y</math> is a function, then its inverse is the multifunction <math>f^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math> obtained from canonically identifying ''f'' with the multifunction ''f : X <math>\\rightrightarrows</math> Y'' defined by <math>x \\mapsto \\left\\{ f(x) \\right\\}</math>.\n* <math>\\operatorname{int}_T S</math> is the [[interior (topology)|interior]] of ''S'' with respect to ''T'', where <math>S \\subseteq T</math>.\n* <math>\\operatorname{rint} S := \\operatorname{int}_{\\operatorname{aff} S} S</math> is the [[interior (topology)|interior]] of ''S'' with respect to <math>\\operatorname{aff} S</math>.\n\n===Statement===\n('''Ursescu'''){{sfn | Zalinescu | 2002 | p=23}} Let ''X'' be a [[complete]] [[semi-metrizable]] [[locally convex]] [[topological vector space]] and <math>\\mathcal{R} : X \\rightrightarrows Y</math> be a [[closed]] [[convex]] multifunction with non-empty domain. \nAssume that <math>\\operatorname{span} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} - y \\right)</math> is [[Barrelled space|barreled]] for some/every <math>y \\in \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R}</math>. Assume that <math>y_0 \\in {}^{i}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math> and let <math>x_0 \\in \\mathcal{R}^{-1}\\left( y_0 \\right)</math> (so that <math>y_0 \\in \\mathcal{R}\\left( x_0 \\right)</math>). Then for every neighborhood ''U'' of <math>x_0</math> in ''X'', <math>y_0</math> belongs to the relative interior of <math>\\mathcal{R}\\left( U \\right)</math> in <math>\\operatorname{aff} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math> (i.e. <math>y_0 \\in \\operatorname{int}_{\\operatorname{aff} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)} \\mathcal{R}\\left( U \\right)</math>). \nIn particular, if <math>{}^{ib}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) \\neq \\emptyset</math> then <math>{}^{bi}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) = {}^{i}\\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right) = \\operatorname{rint} \\left( \\operatorname{Im} \\mathcal{R} \\right)</math>.\n\n==Corollaries==\n\n===Closed graph theorem===\n\n('''[[Closed graph theorem]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and ''T : X \\to Y'' be a linear map. Then ''T'' is continuous if and only if the graph of ''T'' is closed in <math>X \\times Y</math>.\n\n'''Proof: '''\nFor the non-trivial direction, assume that the graph of ''T'' is closed and let <math>\\mathcal{R} := T^{-1} : Y \\rightrightarrows X</math>. It is easy to see that <math>\\operatorname{gr} \\mathcal{R}</math> is closed and convex and that its image is ''X''. \nGiven ''x'' in ''X'', ''(T x, x)'' belongs to <math>Y \\times X</math> so that for every open neighborhood ''V'' of ''T x'' in ''Y'', <math>\\mathcal{R}(V) = T^{-1}(V)</math> is a neighborhood of ''x'' in ''X''. \nThus ''T'' is continuous at ''x''. \nQ.E.D.\n\n===Uniform boundedness principle===\n\n('''[[Uniform boundedness principle]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and <math>T : X \\to Y</math> be a bijective linear map. Then ''T'' is continuous if and only if <math>T^{-1} : Y \\to X</math> is continuous. Furthermore, if ''T'' is continuous then ''T'' is an isomorphism of [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s.\n\n'''Proof: '''\nApply the closed graph theorem to ''T'' and <math>T^{-1}</math>. \nQ.E.D.\n\n===Open mapping theorem===\n\n('''[[Open mapping theorem]]''') Let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[Fr\u00e9chet space]]s and <math>T : X \\to Y</math> be a continuous linear map. Then T is an [[open map]].\n\n'''Proof: '''\nClearly, ''T'' is a closed and convex relation whose image is ''Y''. \nLet ''U'' be a non-empty open subset of ''X'', let ''y'' be in ''T(U)'', and let ''x'' in ''U'' be such that ''y = T x''. \nFrom the Ursescu theorem it follows that ''T(U)'' is a neighborhood of ''y''. \nQ.E.D.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Closed graph theorem]]\n* [[convex]]\n* [[Open mapping theorem]]\n* [[Uniform boundedness principle]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book | last=Zalinescu | first=C | title=Convex analysis in general vector spaces | publisher=World Scientific | publication-place=River Edge, N.J. London | year=2002 | isbn=981-238-067-1 | oclc=285163112 | ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Baggs|first=Ivan|date=1974|title=Functions with a closed graph|url=https://www.ams.org/|journal=Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society|language=en|volume=43|issue=2|pages=439\u2013442|doi=10.1090/S0002-9939-1974-0334132-8|issn=0002-9939}}\n\n{{Functional Analysis}}\n\n[[Category:Theorems in functional analysis]]\n", "name_user": "Mgkrupa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ursescu_theorem"}
