{chem|S|2|O|3|2-}}<br/>[[Hydrogenthiosulfate]] {{chem|HS|2|O|3|-}} (ammonium salt prepared in anhydrous methanol at \u221280&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref>''Raman spectroscopic discovery of the hydrogenthiosulphate anion, {{chem|HSSO|3|-}}, in solid NH<sub>4</sub>HS<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> Steudel Rr.; Prenzel A Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Naturforschung 1989,44, 12, 1499-1502</ref>)\n|Aqueous solutions decompose.\n|-\n|''[[Disulfurous acid]] or pyrosulfurous acid''\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>\n| +5 (of the sulfur atom bonded to 3 oxygen atoms), +3 (of other sulfur atom)\n|[[File:Disulfurous acid 2-D structure.png|150px|disulfurous]]\n|Disulfite commonly known as [[metabisulfite]], {{chem|S|2|O|5|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|''[[Sulfurous acid]]''\n| H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>3</sub>\n| +4\n|[[File:Sulfurous-acid-2D-pyramidal.png|100px|sulfurous]]\n|[[Bisulfite]], {{chem|HSO|3|-}} and [[sulfite]], {{chem|SO|3|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|''[[Dithionous acid]]''\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>\n| +3\n|[[File:Dithionous acid.svg|100px|dithionous]]\n|[[Dithionite]], {{chem|O|2|SSO|2|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|[[Sulfoxylic acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>2</sub>\n| +2\n|[[File:Sulfoxyls\u00e4ure.svg|100px|sulfoxylic]]\n|[[Sulfoxylate]], {{chem|SO|2|2-}}\n|Free acid not known\n|-\n|[[Polythionic acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>''x''</sub>O<sub>6</sub>\n| 0 (for the bridging S atoms), +5 (for the terminal central S atoms)\n|[[File:Polythionic acid 2-D structure.png|150px|polythionic]]\n|[[Polythionate]]s, {{chem|O|3|S(S|''x''\u22122|)SO|3|2-}}. Example [[trithionate]], [[tetrathionate]], [[pentathionate]], [[hexathionate]], [[heptathionate]], [[octathionate]], [[nonathionate]], [[decathionate]], [[undecathionate]], [[dodecathionate]], [[tridecathionate]], and [[tetradecathionate]].\n|Examples known with ''x''&nbsp;= 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 14.\n|-\n|[[Thiosulfurous acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>\n| \u22121 (for the exterior sulfur atom ), +4 (for the central atom)\n|[[File:Thioschweflige S\u00e4ure.svg|100px]]\n|[[Thiosulfite]]s\n|Not known\n|-\n|[[Dihydroxydisulfane]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>\n| +1\n|[[File:Dihydroxydisulfane.svg|100px|hypodithionous]]\n|\n|Acid known\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chlorosulfuric acid]]\n*[[Fluorosulfuric acid]]\n*[[Nitrosylsulfuric acid]]\n*[[Peroxydisulfuric acid]]\n*[[Sulfinic acid]]s\n*[[Sulfonic acid]]s\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MeSH name|Sulfur+Acids}} Sulfur oxoacids along with other acids containing sulfur\n\n[[Category:Sulfur oxoacids|*]]\n[[Category:Sulfur compounds]]\n", "text_old": "The '''sulfur [[oxoacid]]s''' are chemical compounds that contain [[sulfur]], [[oxygen]], and [[hydrogen]]. The best known and most important industrially is [[sulfuric acid]]. Sulfur has a number of oxoacids; however, some of these are known only from their salts (these are shown in italics in the table below). The acids that have been characterised contain a variety of structural features, for example:\n*tetrahedral sulfur when coordinated to oxygen\n*terminal and bridging oxygen atoms\n*terminal [[peroxo group]]s\n*terminal S=S\n*chains of (\u2212S\u2212)<sub>''n''</sub>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Acid\n! Formula\n! [[Oxidation number]]\n! Structure\n! Related anions\n! Notes\n|-\n|[[Sulfuric acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>\n| +6\n|[[File:Sulfuric-acid-2D.png|100px|sulfuric]]\n|[[Sulfate]], {{chem|SO|4|2-}} and hydrogen sulfate commonly known as [[bisulfate]], {{chem|HSO|4|-}}\n|Best known and industrially significant.\n|-\n|Polysulfuric acids including [[disulfuric acid]] or pyrosulfuric acid\n|H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>\u00b7''n''</sub>SO<sub>3\n| +6\n|[[File:Disulfuric acid 2-D structure.png|150px|disulfuric]]\n|Disulfate (commonly known as [[pyrosulfate]]), {{chem|S|2|O|7|2-}} and trisulfate, {{chem|S|3|O|10|2-}}\n|Pure disulfuric acid melts at 36&nbsp;\u00b0C. Present in fuming sulfuric acid, [[oleum]]. Examples known for ''n''&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 and ''n''&nbsp;=&nbsp;2.\n|-\n|[[Peroxymonosulfuric acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>5</sub>\n| +6\n|[[File:Caro Acid struct.svg|150px|peroxymonosulfuric]]\n|[[Potassium peroxymonosulfate|Peroxymonosulfate]], {{chem|OOSO|3|2-}}\n|\"Caro's acid\", a solid melting at 45&nbsp;\u00b0C\n|-\n|[[Peroxydisulfuric acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>8</sub>\n| +6\n|[[File:Peroxodisulfuric acid 2-D structure.png|150px|peroxydisulfuric]]\n|[[Potassium persulfate|Peroxydisulfate]], {{chem|O|3|SOOSO|3|2-}}\n|\"Marshall's acid\", a solid melting at 65&nbsp;\u00b0C.\n|-\n|''[[Dithionic acid]]''\n| H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>6</sub>\n| +5\n|[[File:Dithions\u00e4ure.svg|150px|dithionic]]\n|[[Dithionate]], {{chem|O|3|SSO|3|2-}}\n|Not isolated in pure form, only concentrated solutions have been prepared\n|-\n|[[Thiosulfuric acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>\n| \u22122 (for the terminal sulfur), +6 (for the central atom)\n|[[File:Thiosulfuric acid 2-D structure.png|100px|thiosulfuric]]\n|[[Thiosulfate]], {{chem|S|2|O|3|2-}}<br/>[[Hydrogenthiosulfate]] {{chem|HS|2|O|3|-}} (ammonium salt prepared in anhydrous methanol at \u221280&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref>''Raman spectroscopic discovery of the hydrogenthiosulphate anion, {{chem|HSSO|3|-}}, in solid NH<sub>4</sub>HS<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> Steudel Rr.; Prenzel A Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Naturforschung 1989,44, 12, 1499-1502</ref>)\n|Aqueous solutions decompose.\n|-\n|''[[Disulfurous acid]] or pyrosulfurous acid''\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>\n| +5 (of the sulfur atom bonded to 3 oxygen atoms), +3 (of other sulfur atom)\n|[[File:Disulfurous acid 2-D structure.png|150px|disulfurous]]\n|Disulfite commonly known as [[metabisulfite]], {{chem|S|2|O|5|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|''[[Sulfurous acid]]''\n| H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>3</sub>\n| +4\n|[[File:Sulfurous-acid-2D-pyramidal.png|100px|sulfurous]]\n|[[Bisulfite]], {{chem|HSO|3|-}} and [[sulfite]], {{chem|SO|3|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|''[[Dithionous acid]]''\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>\n| +3\n|[[File:Dithionous acid.svg|100px|dithionous]]\n|[[Dithionite]], {{chem|O|2|SSO|2|2-}}\n|Not known.\n|-\n|[[Sulfoxylic acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>2</sub>\n| +2\n|[[File:Sulfoxyls\u00e4ure.svg|100px|sulfoxylic]]\n|[[Sulfoxylate]], {{chem|SO|2|2-}}\n|Free acid not known\n|-\n|[[Polythionic acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>''x''</sub>O<sub>6</sub>\n| 0 (for the bridging S atoms), +5 (for the terminal central S atoms)\n|[[File:Polythionic acid 2-D structure.png|150px|polythionic]]\n|[[Polythionate]]s, {{chem|O|3|S(S|''x''\u22122|)SO|3|2-}}. Example [[trithionate]], [[tetrathionate]], [[pentathionate]], [[hexathionate]], [[heptathionate]], [[octathionate]], [[nonathionate]], [[decathionate]], [[undecathionate]], [[dodecathionate]], [[tridecathionate]], and [[tetradecathionate]].\n|Examples known with ''x''&nbsp;= 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 14.\n|-\n|[[Thiosulfurous acid]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>\n| \u22121 (for the exterior sulfur atom ), +4 (for the central atom)\n|[[File:Thioschweflige S\u00e4ure.svg|100px]]\n|[[Thiosulfite]]s\n|Not known\n|-\n|[[Dihydroxydisulfane]]\n|H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>\n| +1\n|[[File:Dihydroxydisulfane.svg|100px|hypodithionous]]\n|\n|Acid known\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chlorosulfuric acid]]\n*[[Fluorosulfuric acid]]\n*[[Nitrosylsulfuric acid]]\n*[[Peroxydisulfuric acid]]\n*[[Sulfinic acid]]s\n*[[Sulfonic acid]]s\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MeSH name|Sulfur+Acids}} Sulfur oxoacids along with other acids containing sulfur\n\n[[Category:Sulfur oxoacids|*]]\n[[Category:Sulfur compounds]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4052:2188:1c54:6831:26d9:ceb8:ce7f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulfur_oxoacid"}
